animal.description:
May I introduce myself? I'm Hoyt and I am a golden oldie. I would sooo much like to find my true forever home where I can spend time with my humans and possibly fur siblings (I gave a lot of self confidence with other dogs around me).

My ideal furever home would be a calm household with a wondaful fenced yard for me to explore! I don't like being bumped around (there are 3 other dogs in my foster home and I handle it well, but I don't really want to play with and they sometimes won't understand that I just want my peace). Like all seniors, I have a few medical needs that will have to be tended to!

Do you want to know what I like? Couches and dog beds, anything cozy and comfy... I enjoy belly rubs from people I am comfortable with people and I love butt scratches. I get very excited to be dried off with a towel - that's like getting a massage! If I'm feeling really wild I will occasionally play with toys and fetch. I don't like to share food and toys and enjoy slow strolls and sniffing around the yard. I am good with kids, but older kids may be best, as they need to be considerate about my pain issues ...

I would soo like to have my very own bed next to my very own person in my final home!

animal.description:
My name is Uno....Uno Max. I am about 5.5 years old, 24 lbs.
If you were wondering a few things about myself for one you can tell by my photos that I only have 1 eye, because of this I would really appreciate if you didn't pick me up from behind without me seeing. I am potty trained but I do need to be let out if you don't have a doggy door available.I would do best in a home with a nice backyard as I enjoy exploring outside. I don't mind where I sleep at night a comfy blanket will be just fine but I'd like to sleep with you if possible. I'm a very fast boy so watch when you open the door. I'm relentless with my toys but if you don't feel like playing with me I'm perfectly fine playing with another dog or myself. I love treats and cats(for some reason they don't like me back).I love cats but I think it's best I don't live in a home with them. I will do best in a home where my people are home a lot and I would love to have a human sibling but they should be over 8 years old. I would also do well with a dog sibling as long as they are female and not too bossy. If you are up for my funny personality and occasional human food stealing I'm the perfect doggy for you!

Max Uno's Adoption fee is $325

animal.description:
We have 6 puppies born from a rescued mom who arrived to us pregnant.  Mom is a black and white Siberian Husky.  Puppies were born 10-28-2020 and are currently 8 weeks old.  The 3 whites are all girls and the boys all have masks.  

We require 6 foot fencing and no young children due to escape tendencies of this breed.  Huskies as a breed are escape artists, high prey drives, and dont prefer to mind their owners.  They can be energetic and require exercise.  They require to remain on lead when not in contained areas so are not a breed you can taking hiking or walking off lead.  Also as a breed they are social, loving, and smart.  We are looking for homes that can keep them safe and manage the breed traits of a husky, and manage any of their needs throughout their lifetime.

We believe they are purebred huskies, but really don't know for sure as we don't know who dad was.  Whether purebred or not, they favor the husky breed and therefore the breed specific requirements apply.

Adoption fee is $400 plus a spay or neuter deposit of $100 that is returnable once we are provided proof of spay or neuter.

Please send inquiries by email only to goliathmountainrescue@gmail.com.

animal.description:
I have rescued, rehabbed and rehomed 400 dogs in 11 yrs. Diamond is my only dog from start to finish. 6 years ago we were called to assist the sheriffs department in a cruelty seizure. Come to find out we were doing the seizure and they were doing the arrest. When Diamonds pyshical condition didn't improve in the shelter we asked to foster her and secretly vetted her out of our personal money. You have to understand when they are a court case the shelter is only allowed to do the basics. 
The day the county won custody of Diamond we immediately pulled her into For Bullies Sake. 6 months in rescue after completing heartworm treatment and looking like a poster child for the American Staffordshire Terrier we adopted her to what we thought was a wonderful family that passed all checks. The couple separated this year and Diamond fell victim yet again. Landing in a shelter after being found as a stray and givin away without even checking her for a microchip.  We got her back in less then diserable condition.  Our Diamond is resilient though and has thrived. 
She really needs a wonderful forever home. 
 Yes she's around 8 yrs old but she's healthy and happy. Fully house trained. Perfect home would have a submissive male or be a only baby home. No cats. Fenced yard preferred as she pulls on a leash. She is fully vetted and heartworm negative. 100.00 adoption fee located in Picayune Ms  can have her transported for the perfect home

animal.description:
Rescue favorite Chomp is officially ready for adoption.  Chomp came to us 6 months ago with his ear ripped. Someone attempted a at home repair with a stapler and fishing line. He was also heartworm positive. 
 Chomp has been a ambassador for the breed though despite what he has been through. He is full of love to give and is very clingy and needy but who can blame him. Hes been tossed around and was dumped at the shelter when he needed a good owner the most. 
 Chomp is almost perfection. He loves everyone he meets. Hes good with all size dogs and has even been around a cat and a tortoise. Hes a very chill dog for the most part. 
 However he has major separation anxiety. He does need a escape proof crate. He will absolutely need to be crated when unattended. We are willing to provide his 250 dollar crate if its necessary to find him a good home. 
Health wise he does have allergies and is currently on allergy shots. He has been treated for heartworm,  neutered, microchipped and utd on shots. He is guesstimated at 6.5 yrs old (best we could guess as hes missing most of his teeth and what he does have has been broken and filed down most likely from chewing on a chain all his life. Unfortunately we see this a lot in rescue).
Chomp is located in Picayune Ms with For Bullies Sake rescue. Because of his anxiety I am not willing to put him on transport. 150.00 adoption fee and excellent homes need only apply. Pm the rescue page to see if Chomp is right for you.

animal.description:
Meet Charlie Crews, a 2 year old, 42 lb, extremely handsome, special needs English bulldog. He is neutered, up to date on vaccines, micro-chipped, on heartworm prevention, and crate-trained.

He is incontinent.

Charlie is a strong, intelligent guy with a BIG personality. He's an expert communicator and will growl/bark when he needs your help retrieving a toy from under the furniture. He also regularly picks something in the house to be bothered by and will growl/bark at it until you take care of it for him (e.g. the robot vacuum chasing him as he jumps in front of it or an object that has been sitting in the same spot for days and he's tired of looking at it). Don't let that smooshy face fool you though, he's a happy guy. He makes us laugh every day.

Charlie is a typical bulldog - charming and stubborn. He can be very, very sweet and cuddly with people (doesn't mind being picked up and enjoys belly rubs), but he will also bite if his toy is taken from him or he's rough housed with. He loves his toys and will hunch over them and wrap his paws around them to protect them. He lives with several other dogs, big and small, in his foster home and he is friendly with all. However, he thinks he's a lap dog and will fumble over people and other dogs to make himself comfortable. For these reasons, Charlie will not be placed in a home with small kids and we prefer his forever family have bully experience.

Charlie's foster mom spotted him posted for sale online a few months ago, likely a failed breeding prospect due to his 'vertebrae issue.' His x-rays showed 2 vertebrae that are fused. Although he is very mobile, it would be best for his future home to have little to no stairs. He can jump on the couch, but usually pulls himself up with his front legs.

Charlie is incontinent. He has some control to pee outside. We use belly bands with male incontinence pads to keep him clean and dry. Especially when it's warm out, he will express his own bowel movements outside when he kicks after peeing, so we don't do a full diaper and just clean up any indoor accidents as they happen. He's also on Kin+Kind supplements for bowel and urinary health support.

As you can see, he has a large wrinkle on his face that requires regular cleaning. As a special needs dog, Charlie requires a little extra effort, but it's manageable and he is totally worth it. He loves to take a bath and will even jump in the tub for you. He just needs a family committed to maintaining proper hygiene and his lifelong care.

Charlie is being fostered near Abingdon, VA and his adoption fee is $400. If you're not afraid to take on a special needs guy who will pay you back with all the love he has to give, contact his foster mom Amber at amber@bostonterriertn.org or apply to adopt at www.bostonterriertn.org.

NOTE: Submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston, since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.
Please use the foster momma or dad's contact information above for questions.
The process always begins with an application which can be found at The Boston Terrier Rescue of East Tennessee website
Note that in most cases, we do not adopt to families with small children, e.g., 'under 6,' as a precaution to the child's safety and the dog's safety. In some cases with larger Boston mixes or other dogs, we do make exceptions. Please ask the foster momma.
We prefer to place dogs within driving distance of where they are being fostered. If someone from outside the local area is approved for adoption, they must be willing to personally drive/fly to get the dog. The East Coast division (NC/SC/VA/MD/DC) does have special transport capabilties for their kids. Ask them.
Also, submission of an application and fee does not guarantee adoption of any specific Boston since that particular dog may have applications pending or may not be the right match for you.

animal.description:
Crisp is a 5 month old, neutered American Pit Bull Terrier mix puppy. He was taken to the shelter by his prior owners when they discovered he is deaf. Crisp's foster mom brought him into the Legacy Humane fold to teach him sign language and give him a second chance at a forever family. He knows signs for sit, no, good job, come and eat. He is working on wait/stay and off. Crisp loves to be played with, enjoys belly rubs, and is very social. He is very good at fetch and LOVES to cuddle with his people.
Puppies at this age will require patience and training to become the best pup they can be. Crisp will need a family ready to learn how to train and communicate with a deaf puppy.
https://deafdogsrock.com/ is an awesome resource for adopters of deaf dogs! Deaf dogs are trained in similar ways as hearing dogs!
Here is a great YouTube channel called Deaf Wiggle Butts that has wonderful videos that could be helpful!
https://m.youtube.com/channel/UCNOPu3T62P0Xfo8Z5aAtQhACrisp is 95% house trained! (A rainy day may throw a kink in things still!) Crisp is energetic and will need a family with enough time to engage in play and exercise. Crisp does well with kids old enough to understand puppy behavior (~10ys and up). He does well with other dogs but not cats. He would do best in a home with a yard.
Current weight ~34 pounds
Projected weight 60-70 lbs
Crate trained
We are requesting a donation of $325 for his adoption which includes his neuter, three rounds of puppy vaccines, a rabies vaccine, microchip with registration, dewormer and a single dose of heartworm preventative. If you're interested in meeting or adopting him, please complete an application on our website and someone will reach out to you within 48 hours. https://legacyhumanesociety.org/adoptfoster/adoption-application/
*Due to the high volume of applications and inquires for puppies, we will not be able to respond to or consider interest from those outside of the Dallas/Fort Worth Area.We do not have a facility to house the dogs in our program. They are all kept in foster homes until they are adopted. Therefore, if you are interested in adopting from LHS, please complete an online application at http://legacyhumanesociety.org/adoptfoster/adoption-application/ and we will contact you asap about the status of your application.

animal.description:
Meet this handsome fella named Dingo! He came in mid December 2020 and is patiently awaiting his FOREVER home. He is such a sweet and handsome boy who is full of happiness and love to share. He is around 1 year old, current on shots, and seems to like most female dogs he has met.he does play hard. He needs a special home that can be cautious with him when feeding (put food in bowl and leave him to enjoy & pick up bowl when he is away and done. Use caution whenever  food is around. He is very protective of his food and so he needs to have a safe spot to eat. Also with this a home without young kids since they sometimes carry food in their hands and he could try to grab it out of their hand and hurt the child not intentionally.  We are working with him to take treats gently and that he doesn’t have to worry about being fed. (I personally have a dog that had issues and is now 10 yo and it’s better but the protection of food is still there. I still can’t let my guard down to set up for an accident to happen.)  Dingo is super happy and loves to run and play and soak up body rubs and affection from his human friends. Such a sweet boy who deserves to loving FOREVER home to call his own. Maybe you have the most amazing home for this charming fella that is perfect for what he needs. Stop by the shelter for a visit with Dingo today! 
If you have another dog and are interested in meeting another potential new furry member please bring him or her to the shelter and meet on neutral ground before adopting. No need to shuffle the animals around any more than necessary. Please know that 1 mosquito bite can create heart worms and they can be fatal if not treated. It is VERY important to keep your pets healthy and protected by keeping them on a once a month heart worm and flea/tick prevention. These animals are counting on you as their owner to provide them with lots a love and the proper health care so PLEASE make sure you are aware and prepared before adopting. Owning a pet is an extra expense and responsibility but is so worth every minute and penny you invest in them. They will add lots of joy and unconditional love if given a fair chance.
The shelter is open Mon.-Fri. 10-1, 2-5 and Sat. 10-4. Adopt a homeless pet and save a life. If you can not adopt right now come out and volunteer and make a difference in the lives of these animals while they await their FOREVER home.

animal.description:
**Due to the high volume of applicants,  we are no longer able to accept any new applications at this time. Should anything change,  we will remove this message. 
Please visit us at our Facebook page for new dogs and updates. 

------

Ernie is located in Blue Mountain. 

My name is Ernie and I'm a cute 10 lbs happy dynamo that loves to play and hang out with my people. I like dogs my own size. I'm about 18mths old to 2 years old.  I'm a Havanese Westie x

As playful as I am,  I calm down just as quickly and can chill out as well.  I'm pee pad trained and go outside.

I'm a friendly little guy and quite social. 

My foster parents would like to see me placed in a home with another small little dog I can play with.  I'd love the company and hope the dog is about the same energy and age as I am. 

My foster parents thinks I'm one of the best dogs they ever had a chance to care for.  ?

I love to smile and im a happy go lucky little munchkin. I would love an adult home or home with children over 12. A flexible work schedule (even after Covid) and experience with rescue dogs preferred. 

Thank you. 

-----
Our adoption screening process:

We have a waiting list of pre approved applicants and applicants in the process of being approved to adopt through Snookies.

If you would like to be pre approved,  please go to www.snookiessociety.com 

Our adoption form can be found there. 

We ask for 1 veterinarian reference and 3 personal references 

We do a phone interview

We ask the applicant to meet the dog 

We do a home inspection and help you doggy proof and prepare for the new dog. (Covid safety protocols applied)

Training is provided.  We offer reading material, videos, and live webinars through a certified dog training facility. Successful applicants have access to training support with certified dog behaviorists to assist in the transition process of the new home.

We are overwhelmed with inquiries.  We are not able to answer all inquiries.  Please  submit an adoption application found at www.snookiessociety.com if you fit the criteria above.   Please use only one platform to contact us.

Most questions can be answered if you go to our website at www.snookiessociety.com 

Thank you!

animal.description:
Please note that due the volume of applications, we are unable to respond to all applicants and ONLY those being considered will be contacted. We thank you for your understanding. The adoption application link is posted below and the adoption process is outlined on the website.  Animatch asks that you read the Adoptee’s bio in its entirety before applying to ensure you meet the requirements for the dog.

My name is Thinsel and I choose to believe that better days lie ahead. Life is finally good for me and it is getting better every day as I am pampered with nutritious food, clean water, and best of all cuddles that make me feel warm and loved. At this time, I don’t have the tolerance for other dogs; since I’m not yet in tip-top shape, their goofy antics just annoy me. For that reason, I would thrive in a home where I was your one and only. I weigh 28 lbs and I should be at least 50. I was found and brought to Animal Control by a Good Samaritan who made it their business to help me out. My feet were bloody, I was exhausted and lethargic, and I was in desperate need of food and water. No one claimed me so the good people at Animatch welcomed me with open arms. I’ve been promised a new beginning filled with unconditional love and care. I’ve got some mending to do – I am anemic and severely underweight. At this point, I need a quiet, low traffic home, where I can enjoy a walk or two, relax and let my body heal, and benefit from some well-deserved attention. I am 7 years old and my dream is that my next 7 years will be shared with a human who can make up for lost time. If you have a home to offer me; I’m ready to be your dog. I’m looking for a long-term, serious relationship. Please fill in the Adoption Form if you want to adopt me.

animal.description:
If you've been yearning for someone to accompany you on long walks and then snuggle next to you on the couch, your wait is over! My name is Bella, and I could be the girl of your dreams.

I am a 9-year-old Lab/Shepherd/Husky mix who is extremely chill with a passion for people and strolling through the neighborhood.

I spend most of my time lounging with and loving on my humans. But I do cherish my daily walks. I love to wander for two to three miles each day, and if I miss my walk, I can be a little antsy.

I love to meet new people and pups, but I haven't been around any kids. I could live in an apartment that doesn't have stairs, as long as, I get my walks. I do have diabetes, but insulin injections twice a day and diabetic dog food have helped me keep things in check. I'm not a huge fan of the shots, but I do love to please my people, so if you give me enough love, I'll usually cooperate. That medication can be expensive - about $25 per month for insulin and $100 month for my special food. 

But I'm totally worth it because I am generous with my love and affection. I love to be outside, especially when it's cold, and I'd probably benefit from training, as sometimes I can be a bit stubborn. I am, at heart, happy to do what my people want because I just want a pack I can call my own.

Dogs are not placed on a first-come, first-serve basis. We strive to find the perfect home for each animal. Applications may take up to 48 hours to process.

All CAWS animals are fixed, microchipped, and vaccinated. Her adoption fee is $200. If you are interested in adopting a CAWS pet, please fill out an online application at http://caws.org/adoption-application If you are interested in adopting a CAWS pet, please fill out an online application at https://caws.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Faith is a 2 year old female that will be spayed once she is brought up to her correct weight and health status. She is a pocket Mal and currently weighs 30lbs and stands just at 24 inches tall. She comes from an abuse/neglect situation where she was left in a kennel with with no food and certainly no human interaction. 

She is skittish of new people and situations but does bond quickly to anyone who will give her treats, time and affection. Her foster has been training her on how to just be a dog while learning some commands and leash manners. She is currently not house trained, but has no issues being crated in the house for the night. She has very high energy but has no ball or toy drive to speak of. Although she was almost starved to death she has not shown to be food aggressive. Since food is such a high value for her she does snatch food and treats from people's hands. Her foster dad is working on her manners so this should self correct in time. She is fed separately away from the other dog in the home so she can peacefully enjoy her meals. 

Faith has been safe with her foster's working K9 partner when left alone, but due to her small size could easily be bullied by other dogs. The food deprivation has made her prey drive much higher than normal so she is not allowed to interact with the cats or other farm animals at her foster's home. She would not be a good match for a home with cats and/or other small animals. Faith has been on a 15 foot long line when outside on her foster's farm, she has never tried to run away but being left crated for 2 years she is very inquisitive about new things. She will always follow her foster when he gets too far away from her on the farm. 

Faith would do well with a first time malinois owner, or someone that has a softer more submissive dog that will not bully her. She deserves a lifetime commitment from her forever family that will simply show her how fun it is just to be a dog. And treats, don't forget the treats!

If you are interested in adopting this dog, please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog.

City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is a foster-based rescue in Washington, DC. We do not have a shelter. We focus on local adoptions in DC and the metro area of Maryland and Virginia. CDR&CK has a thorough adoption process in order to find the best possible fit for each of our dogs and cats (we do not operate under a first-come, first-served model).

Upon accepting a new cat or dog into the organization, we provide a basic vet visit that includes necessary vaccinations, disease screenings, deworming, microchips, and spay/neuter (unless specified). We do not provide a comprehensive medical exam prior to adoption. As a result, sickness, injury, and disability may exist unbeknownst to CDR&CK. City Dogs Rescue & City Kitties is not responsible for payment of any vet care, including known and unknown medical conditions once a cat or dog is adopted from us. 
Dog specific: Rabies, DHPP, Bordatella vaccines. They are tested for HW, Lyme, Ehrlichia, Anaplasmosis.

Most cats and dogs will have a house training accident in the initial days in their new home and we cannot guarantee any pet is housebroken or crate trained.

We also update our Facebook page daily with new cats and dogs.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Sweet Pea is not your typical Chow Chow girl! At just 2 years old she was found stray by a nice lady who took her in and cared for her. ODAAT became involved to help find her a home and now that she is spayed and healthy again, she is looking for her forever home! Most Chows can be aloof and independent but not Sweet Pea! She LOVES to play and loves children! She has really taken to the 2 yr old in her foster home and gives her kisses all the time. She is very loyal to her family and is good with strangers. Anyone that shows her the slightest amount of kindness, she will shine it back to you every day. She's there to greet you when you come home with a wagging butt and a smile on her face. She is very prey driven so she can not live where there is any type of livestock (cows, chickens, etc.) She does fine with the cats around the house though! She likes her butt scratched right above her tail and loves when you wrap your arms around her and give her hugs. She doesn't like to sleep next to her human or cuddle very much, she likes to be at a distance where she can watch over everyone. When it comes to feeding time she is fed seperately from the other dogs in the home. She does not need crated and is doing great at house training, with just an occasional accident here and there. Her leash skills are developing, she will start out pulling on walks but gets better and is heeling well by the end of the walk. We feel a family best suitable for Sweet Pea is one with breed experience. She will require grooming and daily exercise. If you are interested in adopting Miss Sweet Pea, please apply through our website
www.onedogatatime.us

animal.description: This handsome boy is Oslo. Not only is he the cutest doggie you've seen, he has a personality to match. He's 2 years old, 43 pounds, and tons of fun. He has lots and lots of energy, loves to play, and can't help but express his happiness.Oslo came to the shelter with a broken leg. It has been repaired and he is now on crate rest while it heals. Even though this has been difficult, he has a good attitude and takes it all in stride. He's always happy to see his humans and always greets them with kisses. He is the sweetest boy you'll ever meet. He is crate trained, potty trained, and will walk on a leash, but pulls pretty hard and will be more trained once he's off crate rest. Oslo has not been tested around kids or cats. He does have some food and toy possessiveness, but with his foster dogs he's learning to share and know that no one is going to take his food. Oslo would do best in a home where he can get lots of exercise and receive loads of attention. He loves to lay across laps, cuddle, and give kisses by the dozen. If you are interested in learning more, apply now and one of our Adoption Counselors will discuss the options available so you can bring home your new furry family member! Applications are processed in the order in which they are received; please be aware that this pet may have interested applicants ahead of you. All Dallas Pets Alive adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon adoption. The standard minimum donation for dogs over six months to seven years is $200, puppies under six months is $250, dogs eight years and over are $100 unless specified otherwise. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallaspetsalive.org/adopt/adoptable-dogs/ For more information, you can email adopt@dallaspetsalive.org

animal.description: For a pup with an absolutely unrivaled enjoyment of life and all its bounties, Rhino is the number one choice! Extremely smart and down to follow on whatever plan you want to pursue, this perfect driving companion is ready to settle into his own forever home. Rhino will need a bit of time to adjust after all the rapid change in his life, but he'll quickly adapt and be his loveable goofy self. Rhino loves toys of any kind, from puzzles to kongs and soft toys - and everything between! When not going to town on his favorite toy, Rhino will be your adventure partner for life on hikes, walks, outings, playtime in the yard or even just drives around the neighborhood. As an eager-to-please and sensitive pup Rhino knows how to adapt to your feelings and understands when it's time to cuddle up and watch some Netflix, making him a truly flexible dog for any home with a backyard and a loving family. Rhino has even shown his willingness to be an even better dog for you - he comes with paid training support from local trainers who know him well to really strengthen your bond. He'd do well in a home without any other dogs to be the star of the show and needs a semi-activate, adult-only family with a backyard to let him zoom freely! Besides the occasional mouthing, Rhino is just wondering when it will be his turn for a happily ever after. Come see this handsome pup today to see if you can be the one to provide it!

animal.description: George Foreman is the lean, mean, squirrel-chasing machine! That's right, he is the one and only George Foreman! Okay, that's mostly true (except for the mean part). This guy is a drop-dead handsome four year old who can seem half his age when he's playing in the yard, fetching balls and sticks to his heart's content. He will win your heart with his big puppy eyes and flop-tacular ears - an adorable symptom of his blue lacy heritage. His favorite pastimes are sniffing absolutely everything, snoozing on the couch, and chewing on toys. Give him something worthy to gnaw and he'll be your best friend, which he'll tell you by wiggling on the ground like a goofball. He can also be a bit of a sous chef in the kitchen and cleans floors free of charge. He's not much of a licker, but George absolutely loves to cuddle at the end of the day. George is house-trained, and has had zero accidents inside. He knows 'sit and 'wait, and can be a good student when treats are around. While he is not a picky eater, he is very allergic to chicken, so be sure to comb those ingredient labels. He loves his crate and likes to cool down there after a good workout session in the yard. George would be ideal for someone with a fenced-in yard, as he is a very athletic and energetic pup and can climb your average 4ft chain link fence when a squirrel or a cat taunt him. If you are looking for a classy canine with an active lifestyle, George would make a perfect companion. Get in touch and come meet George today!

animal.description:
Fat head, gorgeous, silly, loving, playful, precocious, turd, obnoxious, loud, rowdy, vocal, stubborn, hard headed, determined... these are some of the things my foster mom says about me. She loves me, all the people at the rescue love me once they realize I'm just a big ol softy.
I can be scary if you don't know me because I do protect my family. I am unsure about children because they make me nervous. There were kids at my old home but I knocked them down too much.
I do really well with other dogs and my buddy Spazz is only 20 lbs but we have so much fun together. We sing, wrestle, run around because he chases me. We hide in the tunnels, share toys and make sure no strangers enter our domain.
I also love my buddy Freckles and even though I barked at him for a long time we get along really well now and lay on the outside bed together.
I don't crate because of missing my back leg but I do hang out in my kennel off and on through out the day. I am enjoying my big Costco bed in there too. I am potty trained but can't resist the temptation to pee where others have peed before so sometimes I slip up.
I may only have 3 legs but I'm down to wrestle, cuddle, go on adventures or whatever you've got in mind. Please don't pass me up, I'm very worth your time...

Meet this sweetheart named Nala! This poor girl was found out and about on Christmas day, and the owner decided to sign her over to the shelter on 12/25. They gave no information about Nala, but she is great with people. Even though Nala is great with people, she needs to be an only pet in her new home. She is a calm 3 year old girl, and she knows how to sit on command. This 64 pound loving girl will make a great family member for a family looking for a playful, sweet, smart dog to give all their attention to all the time! Meet Nala in run 852, her ID number is 626612. Nala is up-to-date on vaccines, now spayed, and will be microchipped, and heartworm tested upon adoption. Nala can't wait to love her new family!  A volunteer says she is a stunning dog, treat motivated, doesn't pull on a leash, and very gentle.

Nala meets Jansen - https://youtu.be/cM5CbnpwQGI
Nala meets Raleigh - https://youtu.be/Au07qsj1BmI

Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Shelby is a friendly female mixed breed dog - we are guessing she has some bulldog or pitbull in her and maybe some lab? She is approx 2 years old and 45 lbs. Shelby is super friendly with other dogs, sweet with people and kids and is living with cats that she sometimes wants to chase (so probably best no cats).

Shelby is so friendly, and is a happy good girl. She has a wonderful temperament, she is kind of meek and mild, lower key although loves to ramp play up with another dog. She loves to play with the other dogs in the foster home (2 male dogs) and she and one particularly could play for hours. Shelby loves to chew on toys, so we are providing her with bully sticks and toys that are suitable for hard chewers.

Shelby's foster says she is very quiet (not a barker), loves cuddles, and is good with everyone. She does not have separation anxiety, and is easy going.

She's very food motivated, and eager to behave - she's very gentle taking treats!

We are looking for Shelby's best home. A fenced in yard and another dog to play with.

If you would like to meet Shelby please let us know! Thank you!

animal.description: Howdy.  My name is Mars and I am a 6 yr old cattle dog mix.  I'm not your typical cattle dog.  I'd rather lay on the couch than go jogging (and I have no interest in herding anything!).  I'm not much into balls or toys; but I sure do love treats!    When I was surrendered to Herding Haven I was very overweight.  So I'm now on a strict diet.  I like going for walks k; just don't ask me to run.  Well, unless there is a cat to chase!    I am very selective when it comes to my doggy friends so a home without another dog (or only older mellow dogs) would be best for me.   I'm house broken and crate trained, neutered and up-to-date on my vaccinations.  If you are interested in meeting me, please contact kathie@herdinghaven.org

Buddy
Male
Heeler / Chow mix?
Born 2020

NMAF ADOPTION APPLICATION, found at www.nmaf.org/adopt/adoption-application.

Please complete an Adoption Application if you are interested in Buddy.

Buddy is a sweet and handsome pup, about 8 months old, with a beautiful soft red coat with black highlights and kohl-rimmed eyes.  He was found wandering in the South Valley, picked up with his sister, and taken to the Bernalillo County Shelter, which is where he came to NMAF from on December 22nd.  He warms up to people pretty quickly and gets along with other dogs and, as a puppy, likes to play so would do well with another doggy playmate, preferably female.  He is currently about 23 pounds so will end up a medium-sized boy when fully grown.  He was diagnosed with kennel cough on December 26th and has started treatment.  It is not uncommon for dogs coming out of the shelter environment, even with immunization, to get this virus, so if he is fostered or fostered-to-adopt, his family needs to have animals immunized for this virus or have no animals in the home.  Due to his time on the streets, we do not recommend children under 10 as he can be spooked.  He is an affectionate boy and makes friends readily as long as you are slow at first.  He is up-to-date on all shots, neutered, and microchipped.

More Info:  Contact Kate at kmolsbe@gmail.com.

NMAF dogs cannot be adopted out of the greater Albuquerque / Santa Fe area.

Adoption Clinic Location:  PetSmart - Academy & Wyoming, Saturdays, 10:00 a.m. - 1:00 p.m. - Currently Suspended

Please visit our website at www.nmaf.org for more information.

animal.description:
Please note donations using the SPONSOR ME tab will not go to Fluffy Dog Rescue.

To Locate Our Application go to http://rescue.fluffydog.net/how-to-adopt.html

Our listings are updated throughout the day. If there is an applicant, it will say PENDING ADOPTION next to the dog's name. If not, please submit an Application that can be found on our site, www.fluffydog.net. 

MY AGE: approx. 3 years  WEIGHT: approx. 50 lbs.  WHERE I AM FROM: AL (arrival 12/19) 

MY STORY:  1/12/2021  What a difference a week makes.  Copper is gaining confidence and is such a sweet and very chill girl.  She is even conquering her fear of hard wood floors.  She’s not 100% certain of them yet, but at least now if we are in a different room she will walk on the wood floors to join us.  We have heard her bark twice and not sure why.  We have open land behind us where there are lots of deer so perhaps that is what she heard.  Other than that, Copper has been a very quiet dog.  She goes to bed easily and doesn’t make a peep until we wake up around 7:30.  We don’t have her in a crate.  We just gate off an area in our laundry room when it’s bed time and she does just fine.  

  She understands the word “no” and responds to my husband whistling.  She takes treats and bones very gently out of my hand and then goes to her blanket in the living room to enjoy them.  Now that her playful side is showing, she has taken a couple of socks and a shoe.  As soon as you say “no” she drops the items.  Copper doesn’t chew them – just prances around with them in her mouth.  She doesn’t jump up on people and doesn’t go up on furniture.  She is really easy to have around. 

  Now that we have established a routine, when Copper has to go out, she goes to the door.  If we think she has to go out and she doesn’t agree, when we open the door Copper will just sit down.   We trust that she knows best. 

  Copper loves exploring in our back yard and following deer tracks.  She also has a super good nose.  Twice she has buried her head in the snow and come up with bones left outside.  My husband and I have just retired and if we weren’t planning on travelling a lot, we would gladly welcome Copper into our home permanently.  Our mission is to help Copper and other dogs find homes where they will experience nothing but the good life!  For Copper that is a family with or without kids, with or without another dog but certainly people who are active and will take her on lots of walks and adventures.   She loves to be with her people.

Jan. 7th:  Copper is starting to become familiar with what the good life is all about, and she certainly deserves it.  While I am not familiar with her background, the fact that she is very thin, has skin issues and is a bit tentative in her behavior leads to me believe she’s seen some tough times.  During her first couple of days with us, we left Copper alone and let her initiate interaction.  When she did, we gave her tons of love and attention.  Fast forward a few days and it is great to see her come out of her shell and exhibit happy dog behavior.  She is chewing bones and tossing toys.  When she wakes up in the morning she gets into her playful pounce position.  Copper is leery of her leash but with the help of a couple of treats we are able to hook her up to it.  She enjoys going on walks, romping in the snow and meeting people.  We took her to the dog park and she had a ball.  She didn’t venture too far from us and played with several dogs and man is she fast!  Her tail is wagging more and more every day.  She is not crazy about walking on our wooden floors so we have lots of area rugs throughout the house.  It is also going to take some work to get her comfortable riding in a car.  As far as house training goes, we take her out often and notice that she now looks to the door to indicate she has to go out.  It is a subtle sign so we need to pay attention to her cues.  Stay tuned for more details on how she is acclimating to the good life.

Umm.. Hello there.. I'm Snazzy Jazzy.  I am a little bit shy around new people at first.  Once I warm up to you though, I really live up to my name.  The hoomans here say I am a sweet, spunky, goofy girl!!  I've had a pretty rough life before finding my way to this warm shelter. I don't show any aggression towards other dogs, but I'm also a little scared to play with them.. maybe one day I can trust dogs to be nice to me again too and have a great playmate!!  I hope that someone reading this can give me a chance to be the greatest dog I can be for them.
XOXO, 
Snazzy Jazzy

**Courtesy Post** Peppertree Rescue

Vito brings the fun! While we can’t be sure of his DNA, we know this boy is an all American mix!

He is about 3 years old and quite the leg leaner, independent but loves to be near his people. Vito is an energetic boy who is into playing outside and exploring. Throw him a ball and he’ll be your best friend.

He likes to hunt around for chippies which is why we don’t know if he should live with cats.

Vito LOVES to play in our fenced yard with a tennis ball, jolly ball, squeaky ball, rope, he’s not picky. He does great at “trade” and is learning basic obedience. He loves his people and will take as many head/ear scratches as he can get. He is crate trained, house trained and pretty good on the leash too!

Vito is happy to take walks with other dogs and is polite in public. When it comes to play, Vito is a rough and tumble dog and his enthusiasm is too much for children and can also be a bit much for other dogs.

Vito would be quite happy being an only dog, but we can’t rule out him enjoying a playmate that shares his same WWE philosophy. Based on his breed and personality, we think a female playmate may work out better than male. This boy is a love, looking for the right match to snuggle with and be his forever home.

animal.description:
Dudley is covered in signs that life has been hard for him.  What a sweet, old soul he is.  We don’t know his age but he appears to be about 10.  

Duds, as we call him, is a low rider, mellow and easy-going.  He spends a lot of time snoozing between meals.  The clink of kibble in the bowl brings him slowly to the kitchen twice a day.  He is very grateful and loves to curl up in a soft place when he isn’t lying outside in the sun.

Dudley ignores dogs and cats.  He moves very slowly due to an old injury to his front right leg.  The leg twists a bit making the foot knuckle over, which makes it difficult for him to walk.  He cannot go for a walk but he can wander around the backyard, provide companionship and love.  Duds doesn’t kiss but he is very grateful to have a warm home and a full belly.  It’s obvious by his wagging tail.  He takes a daily pain med to keep him comfortable.

Dudley loves napping in the sun.  Therefore a fenced yard is necessary to adopt him.  (No underground fences.)

Meet DYNAMO-Adoption Pending

Rescued: 9/27/2020
Age at the time of rescue: 6 weeks
Current weight: 17 pounds

Dynamo is currently being fostered in NH. He’s a sweetheart who’s just learning what it’s like to live in a home for the first time in his life. Dynamo is a sensitive little guy who is timid upon first introductions. He would probably be fine with kids that are dog savvy and not too rambunctious. He loves to play with other dogs, but again, he can be timid upon first introductions. 
He is learning so much, and is eager to please. Dynamo is a smart boy who is very food motivated, so training should be fairly easy. He loves to give kisses and be loved. If you’re patient and loving, and ready for some fun, then Dynamo is your boy!

Hard to imagine, but Dynamo and his 3 siblings were stuffed into a small birdcage and left on the side of a busy road on the island of Puerto Rico. Left in the sun, this litter of four would not have lasted long and we are very grateful to the man that couldn't simply walk away. He rescued them and asked for help. They've all since recovered and are now ready to find their forever homes. This is Dynamo, he is a happy-go-lucky lab. He loves all people and dogs regardless of size and would be a wonderful addition to any size family. Dynamo is fully vetted and sterilized.

Thank you for considering a dog in need! Please download an application from our website at www.satoheartrescue.org. The adoption fee is $400.00 which can be paid by cash or check.
We look forward to working with you.

animal.description:
Meet Drake!
Male Lab Mix
Estimated DOB 3/30/2017

HEY!  Check me out!  My name is Drake, I’m almost 4 years old and about 65lbs! I was adopted from Safe Haven a while ago, but my dad had to move to assisted living and I couldn’t come along.  I’m looking for a family that wants to have FUN!  I would really love to run and play and chase a ball and…well you get the idea!

They tell me I need to work on my walking manners and not jumping…but the world is SO EXCITING, it’s hard to stay calm.  And all those PEOPLE!  I want to meet them all!  But I also want to please you so I would be happy for you to show me how to walk better and I will pick it up in no time.

I’m house trained but I don’t like being left alone outside.  I want to be with my people.  If you let me, I would love to snuggle in close on the couch or in the bed.  I sleep in my crate and get along with my two female foster siblings that are about the same size me.

I enjoy alerting my family when anyone is coming near the home, and I have a very loud bark.  Once you win my heart (think treats!), I will lean in for affection. 

If you are looking for an awesome loyal companion who will steal your heart, keep you active, and let you know when a stranger is near …I just might be the guy for you!


Our standard adoption fee is $375 cash or check and $385 credit card ($10 processing fee). .  It includes spay/neuter when age appropriate at our participating vets, age appropriate core vaccinations, fecal testing, deworming, flea and tick preventative,1st vet visit at one of our participating vets, and micro-chipping. 


We must have an application, conduct a phone interview, and meet your entire family to approve an adoption. Please email adopt@safehavendogsIL.org for an application or additional details.

Please note that the breeds and sizes posted in this biography are educated best guesses and are not guaranteed.

Please consider becoming a foster home while you search for your new best friend. We need foster homes - pounds are overflowing with puppies and adult dogs that are at-risk and need help. We can only rescue as many as we have foster home commitments. Fostering is a rewarding experience for your family.

 "OH where oh where could my forever family be, oh where oh where could they be? I'm laying here dreaming of my forever home Where oh where could it be? 
 Oh my goodness! Where are my manners I'm so sorry. I was dreaming of my forever home, and didn't see you come in....
 Let me introduce myself. Hi My name is Alcor, the most handsome dog in town. 
 I'm a Southern boy from the great state of TN. I'm guessed to be a pointer mix that is about 3 years old. I weigh about 45lbs....
 I've been having fun times at my foster home ; they treat me like one of their own. But let's face it. I'm looking for a Cinderella ending where I get my forever family..
 Maybe you can read more about me and see if we will match up? Can't hurt right?
 I am hesitant when meeting new people so I need a patient adopter that will let me learn to trust at my own speed....
 When I warm up to you, you will know because I'm turning over for belly rubs or have my head in your lap. 
 I do have a foster sister, that I do get along with: she and I are pals. But I like to be in charge. So I can be picky about my furry friends. I tend to do better with females then males. What can I say I like my women......
 My favorite toys are Nylabones and balls of all sorts. I am a chewer, so stuffed animals and soft toys don't last very long when I play with them. I like it when foster Mom throws the ball for me. Maybe you can help me work on playing fetch better though. I don't always like to bring the balls back. HAHA! 
 I have some prey drive so perhaps best in a home with no cats......
 I think my best home would be one with people who like to snuggle and sometimes go on adventures like hiking. 
 Due to my energy level, I think I'm best in a home with a fenced yard so I can run and play......
Here's me in action: Click here, 
 here,

and here Showing off my fun with rope toys

 * house & crate trained

 I'm really want my forever family so if you think you have the patience and are willing to help me be a better me, how about we do it together? After all working together is always better then doing it alone. So let's hit that apply button and get this family started......

Apply today, I wont be available long!



To adopt this dog, or any OPH dog, fill out the simple online application at https://ophrescue.org 
Operation Paws for Homes, Inc. (OPH) rescues dogs of all breeds and ages from high-kill shelters in NC, VA, MD, and SC, reducing the numbers being euthanized. With limited resources, the shelters are forced to put down 50-90% of the animals that come in the front door. OPH provides pet adoption services to families located in VA, DC, MD, PA and neighboring states. OPH is a 501(c)(3) organization and is 100% donor funded. OPH does not operate a shelter or have a physical location. We rely on foster families who open their homes to give love and attention to each dog before finding a forever home.

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Please contact Theresa (theresa.wadlinger@gmail.com) for more information about this pet.Hello! My name is Barbara and I'm a lovey, hound dog. I'm a calm lady but still have some youthful energy and need a fenced in yard where I can sniff all the things and at least 1 good walk per day. I especially like hikes where my nose can lead the way so I need a family who can keep up! Trips to the dog park are a huge plus too. I like playing with toys, but don't stay interested too long. I'm fully housebroken and know to do all my business outside. I don't bark often, but when I do it's LOUD! Living in an apartment or home with close neighbors would not be good for me.

How well do I get along with others? Well, I met a few cats at the shelter before coming to PA and they make me a little crazy, but I love meeting other dogs. Sometimes I'm hesitant about meeting new humans but I warm up really quickly. Maybe almost too much! Once I get comfortable, I love getting up close and personal. My skin is still a little itchy but it's been getting better with my special baths. I don't love getting baths, but I know they help so I stand still and let my human do her job. Afterwards I get the zoomies which helps me dry off. Once the sun goes down, I'm a snuggler and like to lounge around. I sleep in my foster's bed at night, dreaming of my forever home!

View Barbara's videos:

https://youtu.be/-Pp-DZgmRyI

https://youtu.be/e0Yc2VaSpaI

https://youtu.be/nAy7rRrqdO4

A few more notes about Barbara... She was picked up as a stray in WV. She was in terrible shape, missing hair due to a fungal infection. With medicated baths and meds, she has grown back most of her hair and is ready to find her forever home.

Her adoption donation includes spaying, vaccinations, implanting of a microchip, application of flea meds and worming.

Barbara is in foster care so please complete an application at our website (
www.castawaycritters.org
) before meeting her. Completing an application does not obligate you to adopt; however, it is required. Applications are processed in the order received in an effort to find the best match possible for both the dog and the adopter.

animal.description:
Pretzel is such a good girl! She is the brown brindle dog in the photo. She is a little nervous when meeting new people, but once she trusts you she will be your loyal shadow. She needs to go to a home with another dog that is confident to show her the ropes. She is a sweet and snuggly girl and is doing well with learning basic commands. She is protective of her food and needs to be fed separately from the other dogs in the home. Because of this pretectiveness with food, she also can not go to a home with young children. She is working on sharing her toys with other dogs, and she likes pile them up and hoard them in her area. Pretzel has been playing well with her doggie foster siblings, she likes to wrestle and play chase. She kennels well, with only a small protest at first. Pretzel is heartworm positive and her treatment will be covered by Mountain Pet Rescue Asheville. She is working to put on a little weight and to rebuild the muscle in her rear legs. She would love to have a home for the New Year! If you are interested in her, please apply at mpravl.org.

All Mountain Pet Rescue (Asheville) animals are up-to-date on vaccinations, spayed/neutered and micro-chipped before adoption. Contact the foster parent or Mountain Pet Rescue at pets@mpravl.org for more information.

Please note that visual breed identification of companion animals has been proven to be unreliable, so for most of our animals we provide a best guess at predominant breed or breed mix. We get to know each of our animals as an individual and do our best to describe and place pets based on personality not breed label.

Mountain Pet Rescue is a 501(c)(3) non-profit tax deductible charity (EIN 82-3039637) located in Asheville, NC.

animal.description:
This fella came into rescue through no fault of his own. His previous owner realized that her changing work hours were not compatible with Crashs needs. Crash is a 2 year old, 75 lb., un-altered, male Dutch Shepherd mix located in Arkansas who would love to find his forever home.

His foster home says that Crash is a great dog! He is very high energy. He does well with their bigger dogs and plays with their smaller dogs through a chain link fence. He just gets too excited to play with the littles. He knows some basic obedience and his foster has worked on honing in his skill. He loves to play any dog games. He's been introduced to rally, but he prefers to chase, hunt (low prey drive), fetch, or anything with a ball. He is doing very well inside. He is crate trained but, if he can hear or see people, he barks. He just wants to be with his people. He has not shown any bit of aggression. He is a very loving and playful boy. He needs to be worked and worn out several times a day. He definitely isnt one to just lay around all day. Once he is bored he will bark, bark, bark! An experienced handler or someone interested in dogs sports would be great for Crash.

Crash is currently undergoing treatment for internal parasties. Once complete and he gets a clean bill of health, he will be neutered before heading off to his new home. 

If you are interested in adopting this pet please complete an application at this link https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/24689/generic . 

We are an official 501C3 organziation that does not have a physical location. Our home address is in Michigan, however, the majority of our dogs are not located in Michigan. The physical location of each our our dogs is posted with the name of the pet or in the title area. If you are within 4 hours of the pet, please be prepared to pick the pet up. We do provide transport assistance, however, the applicant must drive 50% of the total distance of the transport. 

The information that we have available is in our posting. If you would like to discuss this animal additionally please fill out this application. Applications that are completed in our process and being considered as a match will speak to the foster home to gain more information about our adoptable dog. 

If you have questions about this pet please contact us at info@MADrescueinc.org. 

You may also call our toll free number at 844-MAD-RESQ or 844-623-7377. 

Additional information about all of our dogs for adoption can be located at our website MAD Rescue Inc

animal.description:
Bucket Buddy

4Yrs Neutered Male, Rabies, DHPP, Bordetella, Preventatives

No other pets please!

Adoption Fee is $175

In the last month we have learned so much about Bucket Buddy, or BB for short. BB is one of those super happy dogs, who has no clue that he's sick. He was picked up as a stray and no one came. He found the shelter to be confining and very scary, so he retaliated by destroying his water bucket, day after day. Hence, Bucket Buddy. Our SCRAPS friends determined he needed rescue, with all his lumps and bumps and asked if we could be so kind as to help BB. BB has cancerous mast cell tumors, which we removed 5 of them! While Bucket Buddy may get the mast cells again, the great news is they were low grade and not terminal. Buddy had years of fun in front of him.

BB is a youthful goofball who bounces around his foster mom's house like a kid at Christmas morning - every morning. He would do best having your heart and all your attention, and we are asking that folks are prepared for him to be an only dog with no other pets in the home. If you have in your heart a special spot for a special dog like Bucket Buddy, please consider dropping us an application: https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/12564/generic

animal.description:
Phoenix (FiFi) is a large senior female Treeing Walker Hound about 11 years old.  She has been passed around to several different people and no one could keep her long term.  She is very good in the house and is completely house trained. She is OK with cats but was aggressive towards kittens when she iwas young.  She can be possessive of her surroundings and does not like other dogs in her inside space.  She is fine when she meets other dogs on walks or outside.  She does have some food aggression so would need to be fed separately. She has separation anxiety when left alone inside too long and can be destructive to doors and windows.  She will knock over garbage cans outside when left alone.  She does like to be outside as long as someone is with her.  She likes being groomed with a grooming glove but does not like brushes. She loves belly rubs and snuggling. Her current caregiver says when she came to them she was very overweight and had mobility issues.  They have been taking her out for walks frequently and she has lost some weight and seems to be getting around better.  She needs somewhere that she can just relax and be sure of a permanent home for however long she has left to enjoy life.

Phoenix is looking for a forever family to call her own. Her adoption fee is $200, which includes spay surgery and vaccinations (parvo/distemper and rabies.) If you would like to meet this dog, please email us: scfourpaws@hotmail.com or leave a message @ 435-764-3534. Please be patient with us getting back to you as we are all volunteers with full-time jobs. Thanks for your interest in this wonderful dog!!

animal.description:
PLEASE NOTE: If you are interested in this dog, the first step of the adoption process is to complete an on-line adoption application. The adoption application is found on our website: www.greenmorerescue.org. You can also cut and paste the following internet address which will take you directly to the Greenmore Application page: 
http://www.greenmorerescue.org/online-form-dog.html

NAME: Cooper
BREED:  beagle Mix
AGE:  10 years old
GENDER: Female 
WEIGHT: 40 lbs.
Temperament/ Energy level: Friendly; medium energy
Recommendation for kids: good
Relationship with dogs: good
Relationship with cats: not yet tested
Neutered / Spayed: Yes 
Crate-trained: Yes 

Copper is a sweet senior beagle with some special circumstances. She arrived here at the farm ready to go to her forever home, but we discovered she has a lump in her throat and was pulled off our available adoptables until we could figure out her medical needs. A biopsy was attempted, but unable to determine if her slow growing tumor is cancerous.. She does not have any tumors on her lungs and has still remained the sweetest girl through all this! We are looking for permanent placement for Copper. Her adoption fee is waived for anyone willing to take this lovely lady home to be another member of their pack. We would also place her in a permanent foster home. She loves people, gets along with other dogs/cats, is easy to walk, and is very food motivated.  She loves to roam around the yard and is such as easy girl to have around!  We don't know exactly how old Copper is (although we estimate around 10 years old) and we don't know if she has cancer, but we do know she has a lot of love to give and would be so so grateful to go home with a family to give her some comfort and love. 

*For more information about our adoption process and an adoption application, please visit greenmorerescue.org.  

***A NOTE ON BREEDS: All of our dogs' listed breeds are our best estimations and not guaranteed.

animal.description:
Rocko is very protective, but a great guard dog. He is completely house trained, loyal, doesn't chew anything, good on a leash and very smart. The problem is when new people come over he becomes protective and occasionally has unpredictability snapped. We managed it when it was just my husband and I as we would put him up when friends came over but now with 2 young babies I just can't do it anymore-I'm always worried about where the dog is in relation to the child. I love this dog and have worked through a lot with him over the years and trying to manage the anxiety but he just can't be trusted with strangers/new faces inside the house. He would do really well at a house without kids and someone who lives alone/couple who doesn't have a ton of action/people coming in and out.

Age: 9 years
Weight: 50 lbs
Vetting: neutered , up to date on vaccines, heartworm negative
Temperament: Good with adults of his own family. No small kids, no stranger traffic.
Training: crate trained, house trained, knows commands

Email for questions: taylorbryant813@gmail.com

To ensure we're meeting both pet and adopters' needs, we ask potential adopters to complete an Adoption Application ( www.bit.ly/DH-Adoption ) for caretakers to review. Once approved, we will bring the adoptable pet to your home for a preliminary visit. We are 100% donation funded; unless otherwise noted above, please expect a minimal adoption fee of $250 to cover each pet's basic vetting.

animal.description:
stray; female; lab mix; HW-; 12/15; 51lbs; 4yrs old

Come play with me!!  Jenna is a girl who loves to have fun!  This self-starting, confident labby mix had THE best time carrying balls around in her mouth in our play area and when that game wore off, it was time to roll over and sunbathe, find a human to hug and or kiss and then repeat, repeat!  Jenna loves attention and being the center of attention.  She was front and center in her kennel ....ready to go and do...and this same energy/desire to be part of the action, perfectly followed her out to our front field area.  Jenna is a rough and tumbly kind of gal and while she enjoys the company of other dogs,  some dogs might be put off a bit by her up front approach of "let's be immediate best friends and play hard style."  With love and enthusiasm to share,  Jenna would thrive in a home where she can be in the thick of things and be a part of the daily action.  You can count on Jenna  brightening your day, each and every day.  Ps.  She has the MOST stunning dark chocolate coat!

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.My name is Jefe and I am a super cuddly one year old boy that loves everyone! I can be slightly reserved when meeting new dogs, but once I have a chance to sniff things out I'm super playful and energetic! When it comes to meeting new people, there's no hesitation at all and I'm always excited to play! I love getting my belly scratched and playing tug-of-war, but I'm also happy to relax and chew on my favorite toy for hours on end. You might even find me hanging out in my crate for a mid-day nap if we aren't running circles outside or playing in the house! I really love my crate and have no problem spending the night there, as long as I have a few toys to keep me occupied. I've got all the basic commands down and I'm a great listener, but I can zone out and get distracted pretty easily. That's why it's recommended that I go to a home with someone willing to work with me on recall and name recognition, preferably with treats! But otherwise I can sit, stay, lay down, and will even wait for you to tell me it's ok to eat my food! I love going on walks and am great on the leash, even with another dog tied to me! I am also housebroken. Because of my size, about 75lbs, it's recommended that I go to a home without small children around, since I have some trouble with personal space. Sometimes when I greet people, I like to nibble on their fingers before I sniff them, but with the right training I'm sure I can move past that and learn how to properly ask for pets! If you think you can offer me my furever home, please contact your adoption coordinator. If you do not have an adoption coordinator, please complete an adoption application at https://freedomgermanshepherdrescue.org. I am being fostered near Raleigh.

Andy! Smart and playful! 
Hi my name is Andy! I am a 60lbs, 5 year old mixed breed boy. I am very friendly with dogs and humans alike. I am very food oriented and will do anything for a treat! I have medium energy level and I know how to entertain my self in my crate when my human is busy. I am also super clean in my crate! I love walks and Im still working on my leash etiquette. My favorite thing is to play and wrestle with my friends! I am good with female and male dogs alike! I go to doggie day care and my best friend is a German Shepherd that is not neutered, since I am not an alpha I play with him really well and I dont mind him being the boss. I also play really well with female dogs. I am very interested in cats .. so it might be a good idea that I dont go to a home with cats. I would do anything for a treat so training me is rater easy. 
We love inquiries and questions through Petfinder but we receive so many is impossible for us to answer, the best way to contact us is visiting our website. Meet Ebony!
This girl is so very special to us and we are really hoping to find her home locally. ** bonus if you're a client ** Would really like to keep Serenity as her vet for life.

Ebony came to us as a new mom but unfortunately all of her babies except one passed away. Ebony was such a good mom to them but nothing she did could help them and that was hard on our sweet girl.

Ebony can be shy with strangers but is an extremely loving and affectionate girl. She is very loyal to her people and truly exemplifies man's best friend.
Ebony is very intelligent and does amazing with training. She already knows how to sit, wait, and give her paw. She would love a family that would continue training with her and exercise both her mind and body regularly.

As you can see, Ebony is stunning! She loves to wear cute sweaters and is eager to please her people. She can be selective with other animals so a meet and greet is required.

Ebony loves to cuddle and be right up against her people. Whoever adopts Ebony will be very lucky to have her unconditional love for the rest of her days.
Ebony is a Rottweiler mix with the cutest spots and puppy dog eyes. She is surely going to win over your heart when you meet her. 


Our adoption fees include the pets spay or neuter, microchip, up to date vaccines, heartworm/tick disease testing and fecal check.  All adoption fees can be found on our groups' Petfinder page. 
The first step to our adoption process is to please fill out and adoptions application, it can be found on our website www.serenityanimalhospital.net, under the "Adopt From Us" Tab.
Please email the application to adoptions@serenityanimalhospital.net or drop it off in person during our business hours. Any questions regarding our adoptable dogs can be emailed along with your application.  Please allow us a few days to contact you about your application as we do get many in on a daily basis.  We will contact you as soon as possible.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Gordo is a rat terrier / chihuahua mix who was born in March 2008 and weighs
17 lbs. He is a happy, gentle and loving boy.

Like his sister Sky, Gordo is as peppy and agile as a young dog. He loves to go on walks in nice weather and does well in a harness, on a twin leash with his sister. He does fine with a 30 minute walk, sniffing along the way every so often, but not so much that you can't get in a nice brisk walk without stopping all the time.

Since the first night in our home, Gordo has slept in the bed, under the covers. He would not be happy if he couldn't sleep with his human. He is a great sleeper, no moving or kicking or snoring. He is a great heating pad in the winter!

Gordo is a gentle boy, looking into your eyes with love, and then bowing his head when you pet him. Unlike his sister, he's not a fan of being picked up, but he will come cuddle with you on the couch or bed and let you pet him as long as you want. He likes to sleep in a dog bed right next to his human while she works from home. If she is out of sight for too long, he notices and goes to seek her out, sometimes scratching at the bathroom door.

Gordo is mostly housetrained and does best when he can have multiple let outs during the day. His foster human has come to learn the signs of when he wishes to go outside (standing at the baby gate to the kitchen, in the case of our setup). He is great about going outside, getting down to business, and coming back in. He rarely barks, but the one time he does is to get back inside, so we have learned to wait at the door for him.

Gordo gets along fine with the cats in the house, sometimes chasing & barking at them when they get wily. He lives peacefully with our resident terrier and they don't interact much, but are fine sleeping in dog beds next to each other, or in the same bed, on either side of their human. Unlike his sister, Gordo has no problem sharing the love and attention that you shower upon him. He is truly a happy-go-lucky pup.
Interested in adopting this lovable animal? Please go to our website www.wagsmn.org and fill out an Adoption Application. Once the application is processed, a Wags representative will contact you, answer any questions you may have, and set up a time/location for a meet and greet! A home visit is required prior to adoption.

Thank you for choosing to adopt!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Sky is a rat terrier / chihuahua mix who was born in March 2008 and weighs

10

lbs. She is a bit sassy and a lot loveable.

She is not super interested in toys, but she has shown interest in small bones. Unlike her brother Gordo, Sky prefers to sleep alone, buried under fluffy blankets, or in front of an air vent. In the morning however, if she is up before you, you will feel little paws walking on your body and then she will gently paw at you to pet her. She will give you kisses and rub her head against you.

Sky loves both of her foster humans but has really taken to the man in the family. She has a bit of a jealous streak and doesn't like when other pets or humans come near when she is soaking up the love in someone else's arms. She also does not like being disturbed when she is sleeping. Those are the only situations where her sass comes out. For this reason, Sky can not be adopted to a home where there are small children, or anyone who will not respect her boundaries. Sky likes to be picked up and held as long as she is not being startled out of sleep. It is easy to get to know her boundaries.

Sky get be a bit barky at times, mostly out of excitement. While her food is being prepared, or leading up to a walk, or when a visitor comes over. She would be best in a home with no shared walls.

Sky is mostly housetrained but she does have some marking behavior
and sometimes has accidents if it takes too long to get her outside
. The accidents became less frequent as she got used to being in our house, and with new routines. She does very well when she can be let out several times a day, and especially after her naps. Sky does use the pee pads near the door during the night if she wakes up and "needs to go".

Sky and her brother currently live with two adults, multiple cats, and one very chill terrier. They occasionally chase the cats or bark at them (mostly near meal time when everyone is competition mode) but they don't mean any harm. Sky gets along just fine with the resident terrier. They mostly just either sniff, or ignore, each other.

Despite being a senior, Sky is full of pep and is as agile as a young dog. She can jump up on the couch and bed, and can go on half hour walks in nice weather with no problem. Sky may have a few quirks and challenges, but she more than compensates by being a cuddly and loving pup who is devoted to her humans.
Interested in adopting this lovable animal? Please go to our website www.wagsmn.org and fill out an Adoption Application. Once the application is processed, a Wags representative will contact you, answer any questions you may have, and set up a time/location for a meet and greet! A home visit is required prior to adoption.

animal.description: Lady is about 2 years old (born 9/2/2018) and is a small (10 pounds) rough coat Jack Russell Terrier mix girl.  When we got her she was not well.  Thin, wormy, itchy, shy.  She is doing much better in her foster home.  She likes to play and is very affectionate.  She’s been spayed and vaccinated.  Her foster mom says she is still working on house training.  She is afraid of loud noises and you cannot raise your voice to her...she runs and hides. When she first arrived in her foster home, she would run from you if you tried to pick her up...she had to come to you, but that’s getting  better with time.  She isn’t going to be a dog that will stay in a crate or kennel while somebody works all day.  She doesn’t want to be in one at night either.  She barks and howls when in a crate.  And she likes to sleep near her person at night.  Her personality is showing more, following her foster mom around, wanting on her lap.  She plays with other dogs, and is learning how to play with toys.  She barks when looking out the window or when outside.  Her foster mom is trying to break her of chewing on her back feet and toenails.  She did have a Cytopoint shot.  Lady MUST HAVE a securely fenced yard.  Jack Russells are notorious for being escape artists!  NO chain link as she can climb right up it.  NO electronic fencing as she runs through it.  Please DO NOT apply if you do not meet the fence requirements; your application will NOT be considered.  We also want her to have an owner that is home most of the day.  Other small dogs are okay but she requires a home with no cats and no kids.  Kids make her very nervous and she runs and hides.  She will do best with another small dog to play with that isn’t aggressive or an alpha.  Big dogs make her nervous so we want to avoid a home with big dogs.  A home visit and a good vet reference are mandatory to adopt Lady.  Her adoption fee is $275.  Her adopter must be able to drive to the Hampton, Iowa area to get her.  Please fill out the adoption application at www.russellresue.com if you are interested in making Lady a part of your forever home!  Contact: jamesejolley@gmail.com

animal.description:
Animal Profile:
Cameron is an estimated 1 year old 60 lb male Lab Catahoula mix. We took him in last minute when his rescue fell through and we're so glad we did. He's just a puppy (we were told he was older). He has loose body language, super friendly to all people and other dogs. He's such a sweet affectionate boy. Cameron is looking for a home with a fenced yard, no cats and no kids under 12.

Foster Update:

He's a very sweet happy dog that just wants to snuggle and sit in you lap. He doesn't seems to have any training so we're currently working on leash manners, the name game and sit. He's doing well with crate training and seems to be potty trained. He does well with other dogs and is a polite player. He seems to be a little reactive on leash to dogs that are being reactive towards him, but if the other dogs ignores him he does the same. I think he would like another dog friend in his forever home but think he would be fine without one. He seems to resource guard with other dogs and food so we will work on "out" as well. His energy level is very medium.

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $500, which includes spay/neuter, current rabies/DAPPV/bordetella vaccinations, microchip, health certificate, heartworm test. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Animal History: This dog was transferred from our Texas rescue partner. This dog will be available for adoption in Seattle once evaluated.
