animal.description:
Chase arrived at his Minnesota foster home a few weeks ago and he is ready to find his forever home. He is wonderful with kids and with other dogs. He is incredibly handsome and smart! He learned how to hug very quickly and he is full of love and kisses for everyone he meets!!Chase's ideal home will have another dog and children as he loves both! He will need some help feeling secure when crated while his family is not home, his foster family will continue to work on that. FROM HIS FOSTER MOM:
You will fall in love with this beautiful boy the moment you meet him! When first meeting people, he can be a little "springy" but then settles down right away. It's just his way of meeting people when he gets excited. We are working on those manners though. He is treat driven and eager to please which makes for easy obedience training. For being a young dog, he is very lazy. Give him a bone and a soft bed, he will be a happy camper! He is not allowed on the furniture here for training purposes but we can tell if we let him, he would snuggle up in your lap on the sofa instantly. He is great with our kids. We have not once witnessed any type of aggression from him. The kids are all over him, and he just so tenderly lets them! He definitely is more of a submissive personality, rolls over belly up right away. We haven't had him play with other dogs but can tell how he likes to play with us that he really would do great with another dog. He has good leash manners on a walk, and did very well when walking by other dogs. He has only barked once the whole time he has been here and it was just a woof. Chase does have some separation issues when we leave while he is in his crate. I think with some training and trust building he will be able to get through it. He loves his crate and will go in there voluntarily otherwise. He would do great with an owner that worked from home for the long run or is home much of the day. Overall, Chase is such a sweet boy, he loves people and would be a great addition to any family!

animal.description:
Koby is a German Shepherd/Siberian Husky mix. He is fully grown at 3 years old and weighs about 63 pounds.  
As a three-year-old, he still has an abundance of energy. He will need an adult-only home that can give him plenty of exercise and playtime. Koby gets along well with other dogs and would do best in a home with other playful dogs. He has not had the opportunity to be introduced to a cat.  

Koby excels with slow and steady introductions to new people. He will need a home that can give him the time, patience, and training to allow him to become relaxed in new situations.  Koby came to DSR as an owner surrender and has had professional dog training. It is highly recommended that an adopter continue his training with a certified dog trainer. 

Koby is a very handsome dog that needs an experienced owner who will continue to invest in his transformation into an amazing companion.  

The fee for adoption is $450. This includes spay/neuter, vaccinations and transport fees.

Interested in adopting Koby? To get the ball rolling head over to our Adoption Application and submit your application today. 

A Dog Star representative will contact you within 24 hours. 

To help speed up the process, please call your vet and give them permission to speak with us. 

If you do not get a response within 24 hours of submitting your application, please check your spam folder.

animal.description:
Astro is a 4 year old, male, cattle dog mix. Astro is a handsome dog who enjoys going on a run relaxing near a window with a view. Sadly, Astro was surrendered because he does not get along with other animals; he just wants to keep his humans to himself, that's all. That being said, Astro will have to be in a home with no other animals and one with older children that know how to properly handle and approach a dog since he is scared of younger children. Astro loves curling up on his dog bed, going outside to potty and play, and playing with toys! He loves toys of all kinds, but he especially loves to shred to stuffy ones. Astro loves treats and one of his favorite treats is a nice big pig ear! Astro would do great in a home as a companion to just chill out and relax with, or maybe throw a ball around, he doesn't care as long as he is with you. This sweet boy is house-trained, crate-trained, and leash-trained and he even knows "sit", "come", and "down"! Astro has done great with the learning the routine here. He is current on his vaccines, microchipped and neutered, so he's ready to come home with you today! Sadly, Astro did test positive for heartworms, but don't let that deter you from adopting! His treatment is completely covered in his adoption fee! Come meet this sweetheart at the Waggin' Tails Adoption Center in Benbrook, open every day from 12-6 pm, by appointment!

*If you would like to schedule an appointment, please give us a call at 817-249-3647!

animal.description:
Hi! I'm Buck! I’m a little guy with big plans for every day! Right now, my favorite things are exploring, eating, and snuggling in my foster mom’s arms. I just figured out how to jump over my toys, and I will bow and wriggle my bottom when I want to play! You’ll know that I’m really excited if I start nibbling your fingers, but I’m easy to redirect with a toy. After all that action, it’s usually time for a nap.
I’m doing well using puppy pads in the house, and I LOVE going potty on a patch of backyard grass (and being praised for it!). I think I will do great on walks once I’ve had all my shots!
I’m also working hard on my crate training. I love being the center of attention and feeling like I’m part of the crowd. I have some FOMO, so I might whine a bit when you first put me in another room, but after a bit I’ll settle down to play with a toy or sleep. Right now, I get up during the night to go potty, but I take myself to the puppy pad if I can’t wait for you to take me out.
I came from the shelter with my brother (a.k.a. the best nap partner ever), but now that he’s been adopted, I’m excited to find my forever home. I get along great with my human foster brothers, who are 8 and 10. I’m also super curious about my foster family’s three big dogs; I can’t wait until I’m ready to go on walks and meet new dog friends!

*Take Paws Rescue saves dogs from high-kill shelters in Southeast Louisiana, owner surrenders, and discarded dogs with uncertain futures. All of our puppies live in foster homes where they are socialized, and well cared for. An application will be required to make sure it’s the perfect match!

 If you are interested in meeting and/or adopting, the first step is to please visit our website to complete an application and read all of our FAQs: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/adopt 

**An inquiry/question on Petfinder is NOT an application. All known details about our animals are posted on their profile and updated daily. Other info would be discussed in detail with the foster during the application review process. Due to the number of inquires received (hundreds daily) we ask you submit an application on our website (a single application can be used for any dog with Take Paws Rescue).

The adoption fee for adult dogs covers age appropriate vaccinations, microchip, spay/neuter if not yet performed, heartworm test & appropriate heartworm treatment by the rescue's vet. All dogs in our care are also kept up-to-date on HW/Flea Prevention. Please see our website for more information. 

2020 Adoption Fee Scale for non-benefactor animals:
Puppies under 12 months - $300
Dogs over 12 months - $200

For additional information, including the adoption process and our adoption fee scale for all our adoptable pets, see our FAQs page: https://www.takepawsrescue.org/faq

animal.description:
Maggie is an absolutely beautiful 2.5 year old, white female German Shepherd dog. Her fosters have been calling her Maggie, which is short for Magnolia, since magnolia flowers are all white! She was surrendered to our rescue due to litter mate syndrome, which occurs when two female dog siblings grow up together.
She is so incredibly sweet and loving, and enjoys belly rubs and cuddling on the couch with you. She loves getting pets and she even gives pets back by placing one or both of her paws on you! 
She aims to please her people and loves following them around. She has loved every person that she meets. They made sure right from an early age that she was comfortable with ear mouth, and paw touching. She has fairly good leash manners, but will need to continue both her leash and obedience training. Luckily, she loves treats so training her will be a fun and bonding experience for both her and her new family. She is crate trained and loves hanging out in her crate during her down time and sleeping in it at night. She loves most dog toys but really gravitates toward plush toys with squeakers, but treats them well and isn't the type of dog to tear them up!
She is curious about the cat in her foster family's home, so we would not recommend her going to a house with cats. While she is also living with two other dogs at her foster house, she is a bit timid and shy around other dogs, so we would also recommend that she go to a home without a dog, but to a home with previous German Shepherd experience.



If you would like to adopt Magnolia, please visit our website and apply today!

https://www.washingtongsd.org/adopt

Please note that we require a secure fenced yard.

Our hours are by appointment only. IF WE FIND YOU TO BE A GOOD MATCH YOU WILL BE CONTACTED typically within 72 hours. YOU WILL HEAR FROM US ONLY IF WE FIND YOU TO BE A GOOD MATCH FOR ONE OF OUR RESCUE ANIMALS AND OUR ADOPTION GUIDELINES/PROGRAM. WE MUST REVIEW A COMPLETED APPLICATION BEFORE A POSSIBLE APPOINTMENT IS ARRANGED. NO EXCEPTIONS. All visits with the puppies/dogs are by approved applications and appointments only.

* We reserve the right to refuse any adoption without justification and not all applications or inquiries may receive a response. *

Thank you for your interest in our rescue dogs.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.German Shepherd dogs, as well as the other herding breeds that we have in rescue, are highly active, energetic, working breeds. They require considerable vetting, exercise, socialization, training, leadership and mental stimuli in order to be well-adjusted, well-balanced, and well-mannered dogs. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings in order to work on his/her leash skills, manners, and social skills. These breeds make great additions to active families who will pamper them, but who will also work with them, as they are smart dogs who need leadership, structure, plenty of activity and mental stimulation. If you are new to German Shepherds (and other herding breeds), please research the breed to make sure this is the dog for you. We ask that you consider the time and financial commitment that your German Shepherd (or other herding breed) dog will require before applying for one. Please review the section on our website (www.heartlandgsrescue.org) 'Is a HUGS Dog Right for You?' for additional information.Hope is a sweet, shy, gorgeous girl. Prior to rescue, Hope was heavily pregnant and extremely scared at the shelter. The shelter was not able to adopt her out due to her condition (and fearfulness) and she would have been euthanized. Luckily, we were able to get her out before it was too late and she was able to have her puppies safely and comfortably in a loving foster home. From what we can tell, Hope must have been kept outdoors most of her life and must have had few, if any, positive human interactions before being rescued. Yet, Hope is incredibly sweet. While scared, she was grateful and relieved to get to safety, and to have someone care for her and her babies. Hope and all of her thirteen puppies have been thriving in their foster homes. Hope's puppies are currently looking for forever homes.Hope is a very sweet girl young who is a little shy in new situations and around new people, but she warms up with proper introductions. She gets along well with other dogs, and loves to play with the household dog. She does well with cats too (in fact, she enjoys cuddling up with kitties too). Hope loves other dogs and feels more confident with a dog buddy that she can watch for cues, learn from, and play with. Because of that, we would really like for her to have another dog in her adoptive home. Hope is doing great in her foster home. She is now potty-trained. She doesn't love the crate, but is learning to be in it for short periods of time. Hope would love a home with a loving, patient human who is around for a lot of the day to continue helping her adjust and blossom.
The adoption fee for Hope is $325, all of which goes back into offseting our high-cost vetting expenses and rescuing more dogs. We are a 100% volunteer-run rescue group and rely on adoption fees and donations to continue saving lives. Adoption fees include spay/neuter, current on age-appropriate vaccinations, fecal, deworming, flea/tick and heartworm preventative, heartworm tested if old enough (and treated if positive), and microchipped.
Please visit http://heartlandgsrescue.rescuegroups.org/info/adoption for more information about our adoption process and requirements, and to apply. Like any of our dogs, Hope would make a great addition to an active home that will provide the love, structure, good leadership, activity and mental stimulation that her breed needs. Because of that, Hope's ideal owners will have prior GSD, or other herding breed experience. Even if you exercise and play with your dog daily in your fenced yard, please remember that you MUST still take your dog out on daily walks and outings, in order to provide sufficient stimulation, ward off boredom, and work on leash skills, and manners.Please review the information in the 'About Us', 'Important Considerations' and 'Adopt' sections on our website menu, as it contains useful information about the breed, adoption fees, the adoption process and our requirements, and how meeting the dogs works.

Bandie is a small senior dog who weighs about 5 lbs and is at least 10 years old.  She is very sweet and bonds quickly to her person.  Bandie is great in a crate and lets her foster mom know when she needs to go outside and barks to come back in.  She gets along well with other dogs and loves to play with her foster mom.  Bandie was in really bad shape when she was rescued from a local shelter.  She had horrible teeth, a large mammary tumor, and needed to be spayed. Luckily, her tumor was benign and she does have a few teeth left.  Bandie's health had been neglected prior to her rescue so we are trying to get her kidneys in better health.  Bandie would do well with a retired person or couple who  are looking for a small, loving, quiet companion.

We are a RESCUE GROUP, not a shelter, and all of our animals are in foster homes. To start the adoption process, email us at adoptions@earstexas.org requesting an application. Submitting an application does not commit you in any way, but helps us make the best match between people and our available dogs. Your current or past dogs must be inside dogs who have been spayed/neutered and are on heartworm prevention.

All of the dogs in our program are inside dogs and are completely vetted including all vaccinations, spayed/neutered, free of internal parasites, microchipped, heartworm negative and on prevention before adoption. Our adoption process includes an application, check of vet records or personal references, interview, neutral site meet & greet with the dog and your family, and a home visit.

If the animal is under the age of 3 years old or has health issues, a vet reference is required which means you must own a pet or have owned a pet in your name.

Adoption fee of $250. covers all vetting including spay/neuter surgery, vaccines, microchip heartworm test and treatment if needed and any other medical that may be required while in rescue. 

We only do adoptions on Saturday and not all animals are able to attend so if you would like to see a specific animal please let us know so that we can make arrangements for it to be present at the event. animal.description:
Romie is a 2.5 year old male Lab mix. He weighs 66 lbs. From his foster home: Romie is a great house guest! Happy tail wagging guy. Good in the crate, goes right in when you ask. He is housetrained, always does his potty outside. Will bark if left alone, prefers to be with his people.  

Romie would like best to be an only dog, although he has had certain dogs who he gets along very well with. Romie should be with a person who doesn’t think he has to meet every dog he sees. 

He would be a great adventure buddy with a person who wants to have fun and be a leader for Romie. He has received mixed messages in the past and needs clear praise and correction, when needed. Was fostered with a smaller female dog and played very well with her but will need a leader with him to meet new dogs. Super friendly meeting all people. Does get overwhelmed in crowds or with younger children so a quieter home with no children is best for Romie.  

Romie has not been around or tested with cats. We have been using a prong collar to help as we work with him on with leash skills and engagement and it is working really well with him. Romie will dig if left outside in a fenced area unsupervised and has had a bad experience with an electric fence, so he would need patient retraining if one were to be used again. 

Want to Adopt? 1) Fill out an application on theluckypuppy.org . The donation fees are minimum $475 for puppies up to 6 months, minimum $400 for dogs 7 months to 6 years and minimum $ 300 for 7+ years/Special Needs. ***Certain adoptions include an additional $50 "Spay it Forward" program. This adoption fee assists with funding our spay/neuter service for momma dogs. 2) Once your application is in, our adoption coordinator will contact you and complete a vet check and home visit (possibly electronic). 3) Once approved, please schedule a meet and greet to see the dogs. Meet and greets are by appointment only for approved adopters.

Romie is available in NY through the Go North Program of The Lucky Puppy Rescue centered in Bonifay and Panama City, FL (NY Lic #1054). The minimum donation $400 adoption fee includes transportation from FL to NY, spay/neuter surgery, vaccinations, de-worm, flea prevention, heartworm prevention and martingale safety collar. Adoption fee payment methods accepted are credit, debit, Paypal and bank checks. No personal checks or cash. Applications must be submitted through our website - theluckypuppy.org - thank you! You may copy and paste the following link to apply: http://www.theluckypuppy.org/adoption-application/

animal.description:
Jasmine and Queenie are bonded siblings and need to be adopted together. These girls are 9 month old female Pointer mixes. 

***They are shy dogs that need a quiet home and adopters who are committed to patience as they acclimate to their new family. This takes 3 months for dogs normally and can take longer with timid animals***

Updates from their foster mom:

Both Queenie and Jasmine are real sweethearts who just need some time to open up. Queenie loves to cuddle and hang out on the couch with you, Jazzie likes to stay close on her dog bed. She’s very anxious at first but after a few weeks she’s running towards you for playtime and treats just as Queenie does. 

Both girls have moderate energy and are really low maintenance- they are okay to be on their own for a while. They’d be great for someone who’s working from home! 

The girls favorite time is being outside - as long as they can play catch on a long leash, they’re happy. They prefer to run around with each other to going on walks! 

In the last few weeks, they’ve picked up ‘sit’ and ‘stay’, recall is improving as well. Both are very smart and picking new tricks up after a few days. They would benefit from a quieter household who could provide a structured day for them. They’ve met our family and are okay with new people - both were a bit wary of men at first but Queenie got used to them quickly. 

Jasmine is definitely anxious around men, she’s not really comfortable with my husband. Also, any noises (garage door opening, Hoover, shoveling the deck) puts them on alert. They’re nervous around cars and need a firm hand when walking. Driving in the car is okay as long as they’re in their crate. Both are mainly house trained, they only had accidents in the morning of we didn’t go outside immediately.

Jasmine (black) aka Jazzy Girl has the biggest sweetest brown eyes. She is very unsure of things and would benefit from some confidence building. She really is a gentle soul.  

Queenie (white) is an absolute doll. She loves to run and play! We take her out on the 30ft long line and she likes to run around. Queenie definitely does best with mental stimulation. She likes to be doing something. 
Check out this video of her working with the trainer: https://www.facebook.com/192380617472576/videos/1148855422199480/

She really liked all the kids she met on transport arrival day but because she would benefit from a calm low key household, would be best with kids 10+ years and older, if any. 

Want to Adopt? 1) Fill out an application on theluckypuppy.org . The donation fees are minimum $475 for puppies up to 6 months, minimum $400 for dogs 7 months to 6 years and minimum $ 300 for 7+ years/Special Needs. ***Certain adoptions include an additional $50 "Spay it Forward" program. This adoption fee assists with funding our spay/neuter service for momma dogs. 2) Once your application is in, our adoption coordinator will contact you and complete a vet check and home visit (possibly electronic). 3) Once approved, please schedule a meet and greet to see the dogs. Meet and greets are by appointment only for approved adopters.

Jasmine and Queenie are available in NY through the Go North Program of The Lucky Puppy Rescue centered in Bonifay and Panama City, FL (NY Lic #1054). The combined minimum donation $800 adoption fee includes their transportation from FL to NY,  each of their spay surgeries, vaccinations, de-worm, flea prevention, heartworm prevention and martingale safety collars. Adoption fee payment methods accepted are credit, debit, Paypal and bank checks. No personal checks or cash. Applications must be submitted through our website - theluckypuppy.org - thank you! You may copy and paste the following link to apply: http://www.theluckypuppy.org/adoption-application/

animal.description: Up for a challenge? How about 80 lbs of pure, unrefined puppy? Puck needs a lot of help learning how to navigate the world and contain his excitement. If you have experience working on impulse control and basic manners with dogs, you will have this smart, exuberant boy shaped up in no time! He is as smart as they come and eager to learn if you make it worth his while. He knows sit, shake, down, and drop it (he loves fetch!) He is working on manners in his kennel and is doing really well. He now sits and waits patiently while his dropped ball is being retrieved, food is being served, harness is being put on (and taken off.) He likes to play with other dogs, but might not want to share his personal belongings with them. He would likely do best as an only dog, at least to start, so the focus can be on his training. Puck would also prefer a home without young children (unless they LIKE being knocked over and having their toys stolen and destroyed!)

animal.description: In a word Tuco is "challenging."   This little guy is BIG on personality and will need a home that is accepting of his many flaws. Tuco seeks attention and loves to cuddle in front of the TV.  Tuco really needs a family that understands that this may be as good as it gets for him and love him for who he is flaws and all.

animal.description:
Breed: American Bully
Sex: Male
DOB: ~12/15/2016
Weight: ~70 lbs (low-rider, but stocky!)
Energy Level: Low-Medium 
Personality Type: Sweet, Goofy, Playful, Velcro Dog!!!
History: Owner Surrender
Good With: Most Dogs
Fence Requirements: Preferred 
Ideal Home: Dog experienced home! No cats or kids (teenagers ok!). Apartments may be ok.
Special Info: Max is good on a leash, good in the car, loves toys and big comfy beds! He does not jump on furniture and will sleep quietly in a crate.

The information we are providing for this animal was developed based on observations and assessments in a shelter or foster environment. We do our best to provide information that will help determine if the dog might be a good fit for you. Please note that behaviors may change in a home environment. We also ask our applicants to assume that any animal they adopt from us will need to be potty trained and learn house manners, although this is not always the case. Our online animal bios are designed to provide as much information as possible and answer some anticipated questions. We do not have the resources to respond to emails with more specific questions.

We are receiving an unusually high number of applications per pet at this time! Please follow the rules below to ensure your application is reviewed; pay attention closely to these instructions because applications will NOT be processed if they are not followed. Please keep in mind that dog/cat availability is currently changing by the hour; you will receive an email if the animal you are interested in is no longer available. New dogs become available almost every day, so feel free to let us know if someone else interests you if your initial choice is already adopted! 

Fill out the application (DOG: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/11/IHD-DOG-Application-9-10-18.pdf, CAT: https://www.iheartdogs.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/03/IHD-CAT-Application.pdf) completely. Every question must be answered, and it must be signed. If you are going to type your responses, open the application, save it, type your answers, and save it again. 

-Applicants must be 21+ years old and live within a 50-mile radius of our shelter at 22415 Groesbeck Hwy, Warren 48089.

-You must identify at least 1 dog/cat that you are interested in. If there are multiple dogs/cats, number them in order of priority. 

-Scan a copy of proof of home ownership (i.e. tax bill, deed, or mortgage payment - you can black out the account #, etc.) or animal clause/agreement of your rental agreement.

-Attach the application and home ownership proof/rental agreement animal clause to a new email and send it to bark@iheartdogs.org. The subject line must be formatted to read ""#1 choice of dog/cat, Your First and Last Name"". Example: Subject: Fido, Jane Doe
Once your application is received, it will be assigned to an Adoption Counselor who will follow-up with the applicant who is the best fit within a few days, or to discuss other dogs/cats. It could take up to a couple of weeks for you to receive a final disposition on your application so there is no need to check on the status.

-Introductions will be scheduled by appointment only, 45 minutes per appointment. The entire household, including current dogs, must be present for the appointment. The introductions will take place outside in our parking lot.

-We will continue to perform vet checks for current and prior pets in the household.

-Home visits will be in person for the yard and virtual for inside the home.

-Finalizing the adoption will also be scheduled by appointment.

While this process may seem cumbersome, it is interim during COVID-19, and it is designed to help us respond to the volume of emails we receive every day. Since we are receiving a high volume of applications, please be patient if a dog/cat is no longer available. 

Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Timber is a friendly female Shepherd mixed breed dog. She is approx 1-2 years old and 43 lbs. Timber is friendly with other dogs, but not good with cats (will chase).

Timber is a playful and loving pup! She loves people very much and loves pets-she is comfortable with head pets, ear scratches, and loves a good belly rub. She tends to jump up on people so we are working on the "down" command. She also playfully bites at you- we are teaching her not to do that. We are also training her on "sit", "lay", "drop", "wait", "stay", and "slow" (she gets very excited on walks and pulls). She is already getting better but will need more training.

Timber has lots of energy and has been enjoying plenty of walks and runs with her foster family. She will need an active pawrent or family and maybe a fenced-in yard to run off-leash.

Timber is doing okay with her foster family's dog, a seven year old female rottweiler mix. Primarily, she wants to play with her all the time! She is displaying some aggression around toys as well as food and water. We are currently working on this with her but haven't felt comfortable yet leaving the two dogs alone together for this reason.

Timber has been sleeping in a crate at night and she is doing very well. She whines for only a few minutes and then sleeps through the night with no issues. She has been very good with potty breaks-she has only had one accident in the house (on her first day here).

Overall, Timber is a loving puppy who requires lots of exercise/activity and some additional training. She would do best with a yard and either as the only dog or paired with an older, dominant dog who will tell her when play time goes on too long or gets too aggressive. We've loved having her as a foster and we're excited for her to find her perfect furever home!

If you're interested in adopting,
please submit an adoption interest application at the link below

https://redemptionroadrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/form?formid=4003

redemptionroad.mn@gmail.com

All dogs age appropriate vetted:

Spayed or Neutered
Rabies vaccine
DHPP vaccine
4DX test (@8 months or older)
Microchipped
Dewormed
Flea/tick prevention

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Arlo is a handsome boy who loves people and food. He is rather chunky right now, but loves his walks, so he is slowly but surely working on dropping the extra pounds.

Arlo needs to be the only dog in his furever home.

Even though he is 7, he is still playful and he loves a good game of chase or tug. He is really strong, but will obey the command "drop it" if you ask him to. He never met a squeaker he didn't want to liberate from being trapped inside a toy - his toy de-stuffing game is strong!

He is very obedient and takes his lead from you. If you are feeling lazy, he is happy to be your cuddle bug. If it's time to run around he is happy to play. He would prefer to sleep in the bed with you, but will settle for his own cozy bed if he can be near you. He will go in a crate, but he is not a fan. His foster reports that crating is not a necessity for him; he is trustworthy to leave out around the house when she is gone.

He is perfectly house trained, but not fond of going out in the rain. He would rather wait to do his business later than go out in the rain. He is quick to get his business out of the way so he can enjoy the rest of his walk.

He knows sit, lie down, wait, drop it, shake and that he has to sit perfectly still when it is time to put the leash on. He is still learning not to pull during walks, but he is making good progress. On car rides, he knows how to roll the window down, so making sure the child-lock is engaged is a must.

If Arlo sounds like the perfect pup for you, submit an application to adopt him today!

animal.description:
Hey everyone! My name is Sophie and I am a happy go lucky 6 yr old young lady in search of my forever home. I am an active 65lb puppy at heart.

I do require plenty of exercise and if I had someone to hike or run with, that would be ideal....if you can keep up! I am quite the lover and everyone says that I am a big goofball!

I was rescued from a shelter in Houston Texas where my previous owner surrendered me and my brother. Before that we were kept outside on a chain. I was scheduled to be euthanized when Wag Again Rescue jumped in and saved me from death.

Now that I have seen love and how it is to be with a family, my eyes have been opened to a whole new world! I am fun, curious, intelligent, and a happy active girl. I love to explore new places and learn new things! With a proper introduction, I am a bit dog selective. My preference is to be an only dog, but I have been able to do well with dogs that are my size. I do like to chase cats, which is heavily frowned upon, so I probably should refrain from living with them. I am a big girl and my foster family has said that I do better with older kids. Otherwise, I am pretty easy-going and happy!


I am currently being fostered in Houston, Texas as I search for my furever home. Once I find the perfect home, Wag Again will schedule me for transport to the PNW. Transport fees are $200 (this is separate from the adoption fee) as this fee is set by the transport company. All transports are done by ground, because those airplanes can be very scary.



Thank you for your interest in a Wag Again dog!

I love this idiot all the time but ESPECIALLY when he's like this. He's the quirkiest weirdo but he's such a good dog. He's still very much a puppy, loves to prance and bunny hop and chew. He flea bites when you stop petting him. He snarls just before he kisses you ever so gently and fully. He's picky about his doggie friends and protective of his toys but has shown that he can learn to get along. He's the 2nd best cuddler in the whole wide world. He's house trained and crate trained. He doesnt tear up his blankets or beds. Cats are not a good idea. He loves to chase. Somebody needs to love him.
Lincoln was brought to us after his owners requested he be euthanized bc he had heartworms. An otherwise healthy dog only a year old. we immediately accepted him. soon after we discovered that he'd clearly been abused. he cowers when you reach for him and is so unsure of everything. but once he gets comfortable has the quirkiest personality. he just needs a day or two to get his bearings

hes been treated for heartworms and has the all clear from the vet to be. adopted and loved forever!!

please direct any questions about Lincoln to outoftheashespbr@gmail.com

animal.description:
Thank you for your interest in dog who needs a new home. Adoption can be one of the most fulfilling experiences in your life and especially in the life of your new canine companion.

A note to those looking at CPR. We have no perfect dogs - but many of our dogs have proven to be perfect for a certain someone. Our job is to find those someone's. Our most successful adopters come to CPR not because they want a dog. They come to us because they want to give a dog a home. We urge all of our potential adopters not to fall in love with a picture. While we like to know what you like in looks, a dog is more than a pretty face. Our goal is to match you with the best possible pet for you and your home. We want to create furever families.

Our descriptions contain all that we know about this dog today. We'll update as more information is known.

Are you looking to adopt within the next 30 days? If so please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and complete the application. You'll find it in the menu on the left hand side. You'll also find a total listing of all our dogs available.

Just browsing but interested in poodles and poodle mixes? Please drop a note to applications@carolinapoodlerescue.org with your name, address and phone # and email. We'll add you to our mailing list.

thanks
the CPR Adoption team

Date into Rescue:9/21/2020
Reason for being in rescue: Surrendered by owners to local animal control
Foster location: Dreamweaver Farms, Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Petey Pickles was neutered and had a dental polishing on 11/27/20. He's up to date on all vaccines and heartworm negative. Petey has luxating patellas in both of his rear legs (grade 3 on his left knee and grade 2 on his right knee). He is on eye medicine which he absolutely hates (and will nip at you while putting them in if he can)!
Weight: 10.5 lbs - Petey is underweight. He needs to gain 2-3 pounds
Height: 9 in
Spayed/Neutered: No

Adoption Fee: $249

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? Petey Pickles is a picky, peculiar dog. He can be moody and grouchy and absolutely requires an experienced owner. Petey is selective about other dogs and absolutely hates cats. PETEY IS LOOKING FOR A MALE-ONLY HOME (NO CHILDREN) WITH EXPERIENCED OWNERS WHERE HE WILL BE THE ONLY PET.

What is my personality like? Oh Petey. We sure wonder what life must have been like before you were surrendered to the shelter. Petey arrived in rescue with long, matted hair that hadn't been groomed in some time. He was scared and in pain and angry at the world. Our first order of business was a haircut, and that alone did wonders for this boy's demeanor. It's amazing how much better (and nicer) you feel when you aren't walking around in pain all day.

Petey is moody. He can be quite grouchy, but once he adjusts to an environment and a person he is okay. Petey LOVES treats and will become your very best friend for a treat. If you have treats in your pocket he'll curl up in your lap and snuggle. And he's very gentle when taking treats from your hand. Clearly he understands that treats are rewards.

Petey has done well with short walks. Given his luxating patellas in the rear legs he is not a dog that can go on multi-mile walks every day. Slow and steady is the pace for this boy. Petey is crate trained. The crate is his safe place and he enjoys lounging in his bed inside his crate. He did great on his transport to the farm and really enjoyed the ride.

Petey is well loved by his caregivers at the rescue. But we also recognize that he is a special dog that is going to take just the right special owner. Petey needs a home environment that is quiet and relaxed. He needs an owner with lots of experience and patience to teach and show him that not all humans are mean. He needs to be the only pet and really wants a home that is all men.

How do I act when I first meet new people?

Other tips and tidbits: Petey's estimated birthday is 9/21/2010

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. A dog house trained in my home may not be in yours. We will help you teach your new dog this necessary skill and based on your schedule.

Please note - we do not ship dogs. If you are interested in adopting, please take a look at the distance between the foster home location and your location and make sure you are willing to make that trip. Most of our dogs are at our farm in Pacolet, South Carolina.

To apply, please visit our webpage at www.carolinapoodlerescue.org and visit the tab on the left that directions you to the online application.

Please note that when screening applications, we look at the entire home and then make suggestions based on what would be a good fit for your home. You are not being screened for a specific dog although we are looking to see what type of dog interests you - poodles or non poodles, color, age, etc. Others here may be a better fit for you. It is very difficult to get to know a living animal from a picture and a short description. Since we are constantly getting in new dogs, this may be a dog not in our listings yet. We want you to be very happy with your new companion and will make suggestions based on what you tell us about you.

Thank you for considering CPR.
animal.name: Petey Pickles

Foster location: Foster Home in Pacolet SC
Special Needs? Ellie was spayed on 12/14/20. She is up to date on all vaccines and heartworm negative. All of her puppies have been adopted and it is her time now. IF YOU DON'T HAVE ANOTHER YOUNG, ACTIVE MEDIUM TO LARGE DOG AND AREN'T VERY ACTIVE, ELLIE IS NOT YOUR DOG.
Weight: 28 lbs
Height: 18 in
Spayed/Neutered: Yes

Adoption Fee: $200

Fence needed? No

What kind of home would be best for me? Ellie is young and active. She needs a family that can keep up with her energy and personality! Ellie is looking for a home with another active medium to large dog to play with and a younger couple to be in charge of (cats are okay too). She'd be great with kids over 8. She is quite bossy when she wants something and needs strong, confident owners to continue to learn from. Ellie needs LOTS of exercise and play time. She absolutely hates to be left and is best suited for a home where someone works from home or is home during the day.

What is my personality like? Ellie arrived in rescue very pregnant. She gave birth to 5 beautiful puppies, all of whom have found their forever homes. Now it is Ellie's time to shine!

Ellie is an extrovert! She is outgoing with people and dogs and never meets a stranger. She is highly active and needs lots of physical and mental stimulation on a daily basis. She can be bossy when she really wants something, but really loves and seeks out other dogs.

Ellie has been in a foster home for 3+ months. She's learning all about being a well-mannered pet. She walks well on a leash. She loves to ride in a car. She is doing exceptionally well with potty training and will wait at the back door when ready to go out. She knows sit and is learning stay. Ellie is extremely food motivated and will work for treats. She sleeps peacefully in a bed full of dogs at night and is as soft, squishy and sweet as a cupcake!

Ellie is young and curious. She is mischievous and needs someone to watch her closely. Left to her devices Ellie will counter surf and empty trash cans. Foster mom is working hard with her on this, but to Ellie this is still a game. She can also climb 4 and 6-foot fences and will dart out a door if she thinks you are leaving without her.

Ellie is a young dog who is really just getting to learn what being a dog is all about and she loves it! She is full of personality and puts a smile on every face she meets!

How do I act when I first meet new people? Friendly

Other tips and tidbits: Ellie's estimated birthday is 12/9/2016

House trained? Dogs can be house trained if they are in the right environment and are allowed to follow a schedule as long as a physical reason doesn't keep them from being trained. animal.description:
Shy yet charming canine searching for a patient owner with a relaxed lifestyle. Looking for gentle guidance to help me come out of my shell. Treat me sweet and kind and I'll blossom. Recommend children 14yrs and older.

This dog has special needs - they are heartworm positive. Dogs with heartworm disease can live happy, high quality lives as long as they are given appropriate care. We think that our heartworm dogs have just as much to offer their new adopters as any other dog and they deserve a chance at life! Heartworm disease is relatively common in the United States, so we are in need of caring adopters like YOU that are willing to open their home to a dog with heartworm disease. You are truly saving a life by adopting a heartworm positive dog!

All heartworm treatment expenses are the responsibility of the adopter.Due to COVID-19 protocols have changed.

animal.description:
This little cutie goes by the name Lexa. She is such a snuggle bug, as you can see from the photos.

At 8 months of age, Lexa is brimming with puppy energy. She arrived in Maine earlier this month along with her siblings, Serena, Venus, Sherlock and Holmes. Because she was with her litter mates for a prolonged period of time, she is a bit insecure being on her own, and will need at least one other dog in the home to help her gain confidence in her new surroundings.

Lexa loves to play with other pups, and is still in the chewy puppy stage. She is learning what is appropriate to munch on, and what isn't. Lots of chew toys are a must! She is working on mastering her house-training skills, and is improving daily.

Update from Lexa's foster mom: "Lexa had a fun day today! She got to go trail hiking with us, which she absolutely loved. She is such a ham when she wants her belly scratched. She’ll roll on her back an do the Superman stretch!"

Lexa is believed to be a Husky/Shepherd/Collie mix. She currently weighs about 35 lbs. and has been spayed. Lexa has a heart worm negative status. She is being fostered in western Maine.

Adoption fees cover age specific vaccinations, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm/lyme/ehrlichia test, worming and transport fees. 

Adoption fees: 
Through 6 months of age $450; 
7 months to through 5 years $400; 
6 years and under 9 years $325: bonded pairs are $500; 
9 years and older $250: bonded pairs are $300 

FOR PUPPIES: PLEASE READ!!
Homes considering Puppies must be prepared for:
Flexible Schedules for Potty Training. Puppies can only hold urine for one hour per month of age. Crate Training for the next 10 months to keep them safe from chewing on everything in your home. Supervision with Children and Obedience training. 
Socialization; both with new people, children and other dogs outside of the home.
Homes that want a well behaved dog, must be prepared to put the time, effort and costs associated to train a puppy. Well behaved dogs are not born, they are trained!  Please do not apply for a puppy if you cannot or do not have the time for a puppy.

Almost Home Rescue of New England is a 501 c 3 non-profit rescue; rescuing dogs since 2005. All Adoption applications are completed on line at www.almosthomerescue.net 

This dog is available unless it is marked as Pending, meaning Pending Adoption. This dog is in foster care locally, ONLY if Maine or New Hampshire is listed next to the dogs name; otherwise, the dog is still waiting with our partner rescue for an adoption or foster home in New England. 

PLEASE NOTE - We will check your veterinary reference, to ensure that current and prior dogs have a history of being kept up to date on rabies and distemper, have had annual heartworm tests, and are on heartworm preventative at least 6 months of the year. Current pets must by spayed/neutered. 

Imported dogs are transported on a USDA approved transport with a Health Certificate. All imported dogs are quarantined 14 days prior to getting on transport.

animal.description:
To meet Lulu

Go to Perfectlyposhpaws.org
1. Click on the Adopt a dog page 
2. Then click on Adoption Application 

Hi there,

My name is Lulu and I am looking for my new mommy or daddy. I’m looking for a friend for life and a caring, compassionate home. 

I have a cute smoochy smile and take treats nicely from your hand, I’m a sporty  girl and the perfect outgoing companion. 

I bond quickly to my “special person” and needs a few minutes when meeting new people but its worth the wait. You’ll have a companion friend for life.

I’m a calm, thoughtful and gentle girl that walks great on a leash. I’m friendly, loyal girl that would love a family with a high fenced in yard, so I can run around snd be free.

I’m the perfect companion for a family with older kids who wants a quiet, friendly dog with good house manners.

I know commands, like sit, stay, come and down. I’m a very well behaved girl. I enjoy hanging out with my family and sitting by your side. 

I’m a super sweet, nurturing soul that still shines through. If you have room in your heart and home I will fill your life with joy and happiness.

I’m affectionate and loving, have a sweetness like no other doggie. I put my head against my mommy leg and love getting pets and ear scratches. I want to be around people, very treat motivated and urn for affection. 

I'm gentle, potty-trained and a very obedient girl. I enjoy going on walks and I'm a loyal companion who posses patience, good temperament, easy to train and groom just brush and go. 

I'm healthy and a sensitive, easygoing girl. I don’t bark, demand anything and I'm here when your having a bad day.

I prefer to sleep close my mommy and daddy, give kisses to thank them for loving me. I will be there for you, no matter what.

We can everything together, I’ll keep you warm on cold nights, we can eat popcorn together and watch Netflix together.

If you think you have the perfect home for me, please fill out an adoption application.

Be My Hero!

Your gal,

Lulu

animal.description: Bailey # 7348 is a beautiful 6-year-old female, Pointer mix. She is friendly, independent, and energetic. She is house and crate trained.  She knows the command out. She has been in foster home with human children ages 2 and 9; she likes kids and is protective of her small humans. She loves affection and snuggles. She came to us with 6 adorable pups in tow; she was a great mom to her babies and now she is seeking a home of her own. She also came to us with heartworms and is seeking and a foster who will continue LCAR’s provided treatment at no cost. She weighs 40 pounds and is full grown. This pup is microchipped. We believe you can always teach an ‘old’ dog new tricks, so we highly recommend continued obedience training for this smart pup; it stimulates the dog's mind and establishes a good dog/adopter relationship. This pup, like all pups, should be on heartworm preventative; an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure. If you are interested in adopting this dog, and are already approved to adopt through our organization, please contact dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with the pup’s name and ID number in the subject line. OTHERWISE, please submit an adoption application online: http://www.lastchanceanimalrescue.org/adoptus.html E-mail dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with questions. Stay tuned to our Facebook page for updates: www.facebook.com/LCARMD #adoptlove #PicMe #petsmartcharities

animal.description:
Meet Buckeye and Brutus! These boys love each other, and where one is you’ll find the other. They do everything together, from playing to eating to sleeping. Buckeye and Brutus would do well with an active family in a home with a fenced yard where they have plenty of room to run and wrestle. The boys can get a bit barky at the fence, so a lower-traffic area would be best. We haven’t seen how Buckeye or Brutus do with cats yet. If you are looking for a couple of pups who love playing and cuddling with people as much as they love each other, then Buckeye and Brutus are the boys for you.  They are very food motivated (and not picky about food/will take medicine easily) and have learned to sit.  
Brutus is 1 yr, 48lbs. 
Buckeye  is 1yr, 32lbs.  (Buckeye is the smaller, brown dog)

Requirements for Adoption:
Sorry but we only place our dogs in the Columbus area.  For rescues/shelters across Ohio, visit:  ColumbusDogConnection.com/RescuesShelters.html
Must be over the age of 24 to adopt.
Your resident pets must be spayed/neutered.

Adoption Process:
We do not have an application. Adoptions are pet-adopter driven.
To meet our pets:
Call our office at 614-471-9000 or click on the pet which you are interested in and send email. We will be happy to discuss the adoption process with you and set-up a visit at time of contact. The foster dogs are in foster homes and most of the cats reside at our office.

The adoption process includes a lease manager reference (if applicable) , a veterinarian reference, a home-visit (in-person or virtual).
If you've never owned a pet, part of our adoption process requires that you call several vet offices to compare services, prices, and availability. 
Questions to ask include:
How many doctors are at your practice?
Can I request to see a specific Vet or would I be scheduled with first available?
What are your hours?
How much is:   annual exam, heartworm test & tablets, an x-ray,  vaccines, a non-emergency office call? 
Do you recommend vaccines every year or every three years?  (every 3 yrs as suggested by the AVMA)           

The pooches that visit your home will not be left there at the end of the visit. We take them back home with us so your family can discuss to ensure he/she is a good fit for your home.

There is an adoption agreement and adoption fees as follows:
 $300 for Adult Dogs (6yrs  & younger)
 $200 for Senior Dogs (7 yrs and older)
 $80 for Cats  

 All pets are spayed/neutered, up-to-date on vaccinations, heartworm tested (dogs), fiv/leukemia tested (cats), & micro-chipped.
Known medical conditions are discussed at time of inquiry.

animal.description:
1/19/2021

Meet Hank. Hank is a 1 yrs old Redtick Coonhound. Hank was originally bred by a hunting breeder. After he was placed in a home, his owner became ill and Hank ended up in another home. Sadly, Hank was off lead and was lost for 3 months where he was on his own. He was caught by Granite State Dog Recovery but not with some fearful baggage. We have had Hank for 4 weeks and he has made leaps and bounds in the confidence department. He was originally afraid of everything (except for other dogs) and does show continued fearful reactions with new sounds and fast movements. He has NEVER shown any aggression to people or dogs and plays very week with his canine friends. He does much better with canine company so a confident canine companion or two would be awesome for him. Hank is coming more out of his shell everyday and seeks affection now and is extremely loving.  He loves to play, loves bones and toys of all kinds and has that silly Hound personality. Due to his fear and flight risks, his evaluation deemed him not suitable for hunting, ever so if you are looking for a hunting companion, Hank is not it. 
Hank will do best in a home with other dogs and a family that will be willing to work with introducing him to new things and people in an appropriate manner. He has started leash training and walks on leash like a dream. He is a high energy guy and will need a fenced in yard.
He is a super sweet and goofy boy that will thrive in a home with routine and lots of love. 
If you are interested in finding out more about Hank, you can fill out an application from peaceandpaws.org to begin the application process. Once approved you can set up a time to meet Hank. 
Adoption fee is $475 and includes his neuter, vaccinations, microchip, fecal/heartworm test, dewormings and health certificate.

animal.description: Meet Norah! She is around 2 years old and we think she is a Hound and possibly Shepherd or Doberman mix. Whatever she is, this beautiful girl has a gentle, cautious nature. Norah came to Labs & More extremely shy and scared but has transformed into a friendly, adventurous dog! As her confidence grows, so does her energy. Kids move a little too fast for Norah, so she would do best in a home with children 10 or older, if any at all. She LOVES taking walks and going on hikes. Her leash manners are still being worked on, but she responds well to correction. Norah can be timid with new people, but if they get on her level, she'll cautiously approach them with tail wags and kisses, especially if treats are involved. She does well with other dogs so long as they're respectful of her space she doesn't want a puppy jumping around, trying to play with her. She is definitely more comfortable around smaller dogs, but she is fine with mellow, larger dogs too. Most new things take time for Norah to warm up to. While she doesn't live with a cat, she has seen a few on her walks. She just keeps her distance and shows some curiosity, sometimes warning the kitty not to get too close to her. She likes to bow and stick her tush up in the air when she plays, then paw and nudge you; perhaps this is what she would do with a feline friend over time! Norah definitely still has some puppy tendencies. She is good at chewing on dog toys instead of other household items, but every once in a while, she needs to be reminded. She is great at self-entertaining and when she hears an interesting noise (like tummy grumbles or sirens), she tilts her head from side to side with that puppy curiosity. Once she is comfortable in her environment, she bounces around with plush toys and ropes, or grabs a bone to chew on. Norah is house trained in her current foster home and stands by the back door when it's time to go potty. She is working on her crate training but has been fine with the run of the downstairs when left alone. She also chooses to sleep downstairs on the couch and is not much of an early bird. Norah would do best in home with a big yard for her to get her zoomies out, or with a very active family we're talking multiple walks per day or some good, structured runs. She'd be a great adventure buddy for an active adopter as she builds her confidence. Norah no longer gets anxious for car rides! Now that she is comfortable with her foster family, she hops right into the car and waits patiently for her destination. She needs a family that will continue working on her socialization and confidence, but she's already made a 180 in just a couple of weeks. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Norah, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
BUSTER
Mr. Buster is a 6 year old 60lbs love bug. He was taken in by a friend after his owner passed away during the pandemic. Buster loves to be around people and will follow you around the house everywhere you go. He greets you by rolling over at your feet, eagerly awaiting affection. 

Indoors, Buster is quiet, attentive, and when you sit still for a minute, he will prop his head on your lap for snuggles. Buster can be a bit goofy and spastic, especially when he knows he's about to go on a walk. 

His ideal day would be a nice long hike with his family, followed by TV-time and a rawhide bone. He would love a family with a backyard or an area to play fetch in. He is great with children of all ages and is comfortable in his crate. Buster was first rescued a month before his human brother was born, so he is experienced with small children and infants.

Buster is very strong while on leash, so owners should have experience with larger breeds. His foster home has pre-purchased a year long training program with Bark Busters to work on Buster's pulling and attentiveness outdoors. The training is transferable and his family should have time to continue it. 

Buster does not bark at noises or strangers, but instead he will try to communicate with you through quite adorable whimpers/groans. Buster is just a happy-go-lucky pup and with strong leadership, Buster will be one lucky family's best friend for life.

To Adopt Buster, please contact~
Info@AllForLoveAnimalRescue.org
(805) 445-3535
Ventura County, CA.

animal.description: Hi! I'm Rupert & I have the cutest personality! I'll be 3 years old on Valentine's Day, 2021. I've grown up in foster care, but it's just not the same as having my very own human to adore. I let my foster mom know when it's potty time with this cute little whiney groan. (I must have husky in my genes because sometimes I sound like I'm actually talking!) I'm respectful of assertive dogs but when paired with a more submissive dog, I will play too rough & the other dog doesn't want to play with me anymore. I can get pretty excited at play time but when it's time to go to bed, I'm quiet & calm in my kennel. I love doing zoomies; playing "shake the toy like a ragdoll"; & nobody knows how I learned, but I fetch, too! If I'm jumpy, just tell me to sit & I'll sit & beg for affection with my beautiful green eyes & happy smile. I absolutely love a fresh clean bed & spend time fluffing it before I curl up for a nap. Oh, and I'm very treat motivated so just wanted to make sure they're always stocked!

animal.description:
Apply at: 
heartsforpawsrescue.com/adopt

Meet Angel. Angel was rescued from the Porterville shelter before coming to Hearts for Paws.

Heres what her foster has to say: 

“She is the definition of the perfect home dog. She is more than content to sit at home with her owners on a comfy couch and cuddle all day, but she also has tons of energy and is always ready for a long walk or even a run. I have taken Angel on several 2-3 mile runs on flat pavement and she has kept up well running along at an 8 minute pace! 

She doesn’t seem to be interested in any balls or tugging on toys. (However, this has been great when I take her to the soccer fields because she doesn’t care about the balls enough to interrupt a game.) But also means exercise is pretty much walks or runs.

Angel is a quick learner and understands basic commands like sit, stop/no, and stay (when she’s motivated). Angel also knows a fancy, untrained trick which is the ability to open some closed doors —  this has definitely kept me on my toes at times!

Angel is not interested in running away, but more determined to be with her people. I have left her home with the doors locked on one occasion and came home to find some paw marks on the inside of my front and rear door. She gets really sad when her owner leaves. Once home, she was super ecstatic and very happy to have her people back with her again. 

Angel loves everyone she meets (as long as they are willing to give her belly rubs), but she always listens to her owner and comes when needed. 

She also really enjoys bath time, but I have yet to see how she does with larger bodies of water like a lake or the ocean. As long as she’s with her owner, I’m sure she’d be loving it!

We know Angel used to live with another dog. On leash she doesn’t lunge after other dogs or other people, but she will get excited when she sees the occasional squirrel (make sure to hold on tight for these). 

Angel will need to be in a pet-free home due to two separate incidences with smaller dogs. She has met and interacted with many dogs without issue, but due to the incidences will need to work on muzzle training before being reintegrated with dogs. She is not a dog park dog, but we would love for her to remain social with dogs by going on parallel walks.

Angel is the perfect life partner for anyone who enjoys a lot of outdoor activity and the occasional at home day. She could be a great family dog, but she does tend to jump up when excited, so she might not be great with small kids. She loves big yards that she can run around in and loves taking a snooze on a couch or on her owner’s bed.”

$250 adoption donation — spayed, vaccinated, microchipped, flea tick treated / dewormed.

animal.description:
Sweet as can be! Just like my name, which is Honey. I am an adult Pit Bull mix that was transferred here from another shelter. The home I was living in was full of dogs and we needed to relocate. A few of my friends and I made our way here to find new homes. I am fearful of new things and people, so I ask that you take it slow with me. I do warm up and am quite affectionate. I love snacks and take them so nicely. I will need a home with children over 12 years old due to my fearful behavior and sensitivities with handling. I would also appreciate a family that is a little more experienced to help me adjust nicely. I probably will take extra time to get used to a new home! I am not friendly with cats, so I would like a home without them. I do LOVE dogs and seem to come out of my shell when around them. I like to play and run around with them, so another playful canine friend would be awesome to have!

Medical: Honey has 2 small bumps on the top of her head.  They were evaluated during her time at HSHA and look to be the result of an old wound/ scar tissue.  An adopter should monitor them and have them evaluated by their veterinarian if they begin to grow or change.  They may require surgical removal in the future.  An adopter will be responsible for any future medical treatment or care.

He is goofy, fun and vocal when he gets excited (so no apartments or condos for him). Beacher attaches quickly and wants to be right next to his person, which can lead to him being underfoot. Beacher has a slight limp on his front left leg. It is likely an old injury. He uses his leg, puts weight on it, loves to go on long walks, play and jumps around when excited... in short, he does not appear to be in any pain and it doesn't slow him down one bit. The best way to manage it is to keep his weight down and joint support supplements. Beacher is about 6 years young and weighs 10 lbs. Beacher will be great as an only dog or with a female dog companion. Beacher needs an adult-only home. Beacher is looking for his forever buddy. animal.description:
Rosie is an athletic, mischievous and smart 2.5 year old Chihuahua who weighs 15 lbs. She isn’t just another pretty face, she’s got the brains behind those eyes to back her up! She enjoys a challenge and is always ready to learn something new.  

Rosie is an active lady, not overly so, just the right amount to enjoy a home that likes to play with her, let her do zoomies in the back yard or go on lots of walks! She’s extremely athletic and with the smarts to figure out how to jump on the counter if given the opportunity! A good sized, fenced yard is necessary or an exercise regimen that would include some running every day. 

Rosie needs a strong alpha human to keep her in line, and preferably a larger alpha dog to play with as she’s rather bossy with dogs her size or smaller! She is very protective and possessive of her human’s, her pack leader will need to ensure she knows that it isn’t her job to guard!

She is an excellent watchdog, always on the alert, and will let you know when someone is encroaching on her home. Rosie is house trained, knows some basic commands and comes when called. She does well in a crate, sleeps in bed all night and wakes up happy and ready to start the day. 

She is UTD on shots, on HW preventative, and spayed.Her adoption donation is $250.00.

If you are interested in the above dog, please do not email us and tell us that you are interested, but submit an adoption application. The link for the application is below.

To submit an application go here……chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application/An application must be submitted and approved before a meet-n-greet can be scheduled.

Your current dogs/cats must be spayed or neutered unless a veterinarian has determined that your current pet(s) should not be fixed due to medical reasons. They must also be up-to-date on shots and on HW preventative.

Reference checks and a home visit are required so SE dogs can only be adopted in NC/SC, VA MD and GA.

He came into the shelter as a lost dog on Dec. 15, and the officer who picked him up as he roamed the neighborhood knew where he lived and thought his family would come for him, but they have not. He is a really good boy and can't understand why he's in the loud shelter. Jarvis is about 3 years old and weighs 68 pounds. He is up-to-date on vaccinations, now neutered and will microchipped upon adoption. Sadly he has tested positive for heartworms but with treatment he should be good as new in no time. Please speak to your veterinarian regarding treatment options. Come meet him in Run 87 using ID#626491.

Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers. 

This pet and many others are available for adoption from the Cobb County Animal Shelter 1060 Al Bishop Dr. Marietta, GA 30008, call (770) 499-4136 for more information. Shelter hours are: Tues. - Sun. 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. by appointment only until further notice, CLOSED Mondays & Holidays.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.

Melvin makes his foster home a merry home. The 5-year-old former stray packs his solid 70-pound frame full of happiness, playfulness and loving, and counts cuddling with his foster mom as one of his preferred pastimes. Add his favorite snacks, from chicken jerky to pupperoni dog treats, to the mix when they're watching TV and he's in doggy heaven. He gets along easily with other dogs and although he likes toys, he's not passionate about them, but he does enjoy going for walks and runs, walking well on his leash and responding quickly to corrections - with the help of some treats -- if he gets too rambunctious. On his best behavior inside, he sits politely, takes food gently, eats heartily, free roams with a Kong for company when his foster mom is out and is fully housetrained. Now all Melvin needs is a home with a securely fenced yard or one with an active family to keep him well loved and well exercised fur-ever.

Animal Rescue of the Rockies believes that every pet should find a wonderful, caring home. To ensure each pet finds the best possible home, we ask that you fill out our Adoption Application so we can learn more about you and your household. We review each application we receive and will contact you within 48 hours. If your home sounds like a good match for you and the pet,

the next step is to set up a "meet and greet." After meeting the pet, if you would like to proceed with adopting, we'll ask that you read and sign our Adoption Agreement and pay the adoption fee. Our adoption fees help cover the costs of saving more lives!

A home visit will be scheduled within one week of your new pet going home with you.

The adoption fee for this pet is $300. Our adoption fee covers the following:

- Spay/Neuter, Microchip

- DAPP vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for all DAPP boosters after adoption.

- Rabies vaccinations as age appropriate for dog - adopter shall be responsible for any rabies vaccinations after adoption.

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an adoption application by clicking

here

.

We want our pets to go to a lifelong new home, so thank you for your patience during the adoption process!

Please email ARRColorado@gmail.com for more information, as we can not accept calls at this time.

Our adoption process is:

1. Fill out our Adoption Application online. We'll contact you within 48 hours to answer any questions you may have about the pet.

2. If the pet looks like a great match, we'll schedule a meet and greet and ask you to fill out our online Adoption Agreement if you'd like to proceed with adopting. Once you've completed the Adoption Agreement and pay the pet's Adoption Fee, you can arrange to pick up your new furry family member!

animal.description:
To be considered for adopting a dog from Canine Lifeline, you must have an approved application must be on file. Please visit http://www.caninelifeline.org/adoption-process/ for more information about our adoption process and to submit an online application.

Rachel is an adorable 1 year-old Retriever mix girl who came into an overcrowded rural county dog shelter along with her siblings, Lacy and Chuckles. We have no history on their pre-shelter life but the pups were very frightened at the shelter so made the trip to Canine Lifeline so they could relax in a foster home while searching for permanent new homes. Rachel is the shyest of the three and after two weeks with us, is still hesitant to let her guard down and trust new people. She loves other dogs so definitely needs a home with a canine buddy who can show her the ropes and help boost her confidence in new situations. Rachel also needs a home in quiet neighborhood or rural area as a busy urban or bustling high-density suburban neighborhood would be very frightening for her. Given her skittishness, she needs to have a yard with a secure aboveground fence to keep her safe at home. Rachel has been working on walking on a leash but is still not comfortable with that. She flattens to the ground but having a canine buddy to walk with will definitely help her realize that going for a walk is lots of fun. Rachel and her siblings likely lived their lives outdoors before coming to the shelter so all aspects of indoor life have been new to Rachel. She has been working on crate-training and housetraining in her foster home and will need to continue both in her new home. Rachel is going to need a very kind and patient person or family to give her the time and space she needs to be comfortable in her new surroundings. While there doesn't seem to be a mean bone in her body, it is going to take awhile for her to trust people and that is something that can't be rushed. Rachel weighs about 31 pounds and her adoption fee is $350. She's spayed, heartworm negative and on monthly preventative, up to date on vaccinations including bivalent canine influenza, wormed, on flea and tick preventative, and microchipped. As part of the adoption process, all adopters must commit to a two-week adjustment period to make sure it's a great match before the adoption is finalized. Please email info@caninelifeline.org if you're interested in Rachel. An approved application is required before we schedule meets with any of our dogs. Please note that we don't place our dogs in homes with children under 7 years of age. We correspond via email so please check your junkmail or spam folder to make sure our reply hasn't landed in there. Please visit our website at www.caninelifeline.org to see more photos of Rachel and to submit an online application if you live in Northeast OH.

animal.description:
Meera is a 10ish year old small pit mix girl. She came to us the day she was scheduled to be euthanized at an overcrowded shelter in Kansas. We were able to get her tumor biopsied and discovered that while it is cancer, it is also low grade so she was given a 3 year prognosis -- which is great news. She needs to go through heartworm treatment and be spayed, but you wouldn't know she had dealt with any hardships at all with her amazing personality! She adores all people and does okay with most dogs. She can be sassy with some at first but redirects well, so would need to meet any other animals in her home. Meera thinks couches and dog beds are the bee's knees and just wants a place to lay her head and get lots of attention in her retirement years. If you're interested in giving this sweet girl a loving home, please put in an adoption application at www.foreverhomedogs.org!All adoptions are $200 per dog which include spay/neuter, micro-chipped and up-to-date on required shots. 

Senior dogs, at our discretion, are adopted out at $100 per dog because we know they will have less time with your family and may eventually have more needs as they get older. But we feel these dogs deserve to live out the rest of their lives as part of a loving family.

animal.description:
Please read the dog's entire bio before you apply.  Sadly, we are no longer able to respond to every application, but will contact the one that is a good match within 3 days.
Mr Bean is a male 6-7 yr old chihuahua, a middle aged ittle boy.  He is loving, social and super cute but he does also have a mind of his own and likes to be the boss.   Mr. Bean is just under 8 lbs.  He loves strutting around like a much bigger dog.  He is ok with non-bossy male dogs as he can be pretty bossy himself, female dogs would be best.  He is food possessive, so no small children please.    Mr Bean has a heart murmur, he is not on any medication and it does not bother him one bit, but its hard to predict what the future holds.    He also has some disk issues on his back, since we dont know anything about his past we dont know when it happened but we do know that he is painful at times and to keep pain to a minimal we do have to keep him at a good weight (he cant get too heavy). 
Most of our dogs are not available to an out of the area adoption because of difficulty to follow up.  If you do not live within a 2 hr drive of Orange County, please email us before applying to see if the dog you are interested is may be a candidate for long distance adoption.    We only make consider long distance adoptions for dogs who have been in our rescue for 6 plus months with no local candidates.
If you are interested in adopting one of our rescues, please visit our main website for adoption procedures at www.pupsandpals.net and then fill out our application.  Please note that we are all volunteers so it may take up to 3 days to process your application, but you will hear back from us if your application is a good match for the pet. 
We do not have a shelter so individual appointments must be made to meet the pet you are interested in.  Our pets are fostered/boarded all over LA and Orange County.  
This pet is altered, vaccinated, microchipped, and has had a brief temperament evaluation to help us determine what type of  a home he/she would thrive in.  Please note that we put lots of time and effort to make sure our pets are ready to be someone's perfect pet before they go home.... and to make sure that we will have the best possible match for this pet we do require an : application, interview, adoption fee and in some case a home check.  
Listed for adoption: 1/1/2021
Adoption fee: $250
PLEASE DO NOT call or email to see if a pet is available.  We update our pages daily so if he/she is pictured here in the available dogs section, we are accepting applications at this time.
