animal.description:
HOLLY:

Holly is a sweet and loving girl who is learning how to be loved. This sweetheart is a 2-year-old German Shepherd mix. She arrived at LaMancha scared and it was clear that she hasn’t known much love in her short life. Now, with all the love she’s received from the volunteers, she has been opening up and showing her playful, silly side. Holly would love to go to a home where she is given time to adjust and learn that new things aren’t scary. She has gained so much confidence in her short time at LaMancha! She will truly blossom in her own home. Holly would do best in home with a quieter environment, because she is learning how to be a treasured dog, and not just a dog nobody cared about before rescue saved her life. Holly is looking for a family to help her gain her confidence and learn what it means to be loved. 

If you have already fallen in love with Holly and can’t wait to meet her, please email Rescue@LamanchaAnimalRescue.org and subject line: Holly


Spayed, UTD vaccinations, microchipped, wormed.

Housetrained.

animal.description:
Please contact Jo Ellen (hwbdogrescue@aol.com) for more information about this pet.Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **
Chilo is a handsome 8-month-old Hound blend. He was found as a stray in a small town in Mexico where he faced a sad life of starvation and abuse. A Good Samaritan in that area stepped in to change his fate and contacted our rescue for assistance. Chilo was immediately transported to Texas and hospitalized because he had contracted both distemper and parvo. He beat the odds by surviving two deadly diseases. As a result of the distemper, Chilo does have a minor neurological twitch that does not impact his daily activity level. Chilo also did test positive for ehrlichia which is a bacteria infection caused by a tick bite and he is completing a 30-day course of doxycycline. Chilo is initially shy but once you offer him treats, he quickly displays his affectionate and loyal nature. He is an active and playful boy but will need leash training. His ideal owner would lead an active lifestyle and include Chilo in daily walks, hikes, etc.
Please understand you are committing to providing a good home for his entire life (up to 15+ years or more.)
You must be committed to housebreaking, age-appropriate enrichment and exercise, leash training, grooming needs, and positive socialization.
His adoption fee is $175. This includes his neuter surgery, rabies vaccination, Nobivac Canine 1-DAPP vaccination, Nobivac Intra-Trac 3 vaccination, Drontal Plus, IDEXX SNAP 4Dx Plus Test, Tri-Heart Plus chewable tablet, 24PetWatch microchip, leash and collar, and a trial offer for 24PetWatch Pet Insurance.
Please be aware that puppies and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so interested parties are encouraged to apply online at www.saspca.org.
Please ensure your application is complete before submitting. We do verify property ownership, landlord references, apartment/HOA restrictions, veterinary references, and criminal histories.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio TX 78232. Event hours are 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m.
Additional questions may be directed to sagdinfo@gmail.com.
** This dog is in a foster home in San Antonio, TX. Prospective adopters must be able to travel to San Antonio to complete the adoption process. Please apply online at http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/ **

- IMPORTANT INFORMATION -

SASPCA Homeward Bound Dog Rescue and San Antonio Great Dane Rescue are 501(c)(3) foster-based rescue groups based in San Antonio, Texas.

Our group focuses on assisting open admission shelters in South Texas where over 32,000 dogs and cats are euthanized each year.Our puppies and dogs are completely vetted and live in foster homes. They are spayed/neutered, vaccinated, microchipped, dewormed, and adults dogs are tested for heartworm disease.All adoptions include one month of flea and heartworm preventative, leash and collar, and opportunity to enroll in a 30-day trial of pet insurance.
Our adoption events are held each Saturday at Petco located in the Northwoods Shopping Center at 18138 San Pedro Ave, San Antonio, TX 78232. Event hours are typically 11:00 a.m. to 4:00 p.m.

We also host additional adoption events throughout the year. Please visit our Facebook pages for the most current event schedules.

https://m.facebook.com/HomewardBoundDogRescue/?tsid=0.11494693985281179&source=typeahead

https://m.facebook.com/profile.php?id=185497084826453&tsid=0.7626298417270982&source=typeahead

If your adoption application is approved, we hold your chosen pet for one hour past the event start time to allow for travel time from the Austin area.

We are an all-volunteer organization and do not currently have the resources to process out-of-state adoptions.

Our puppies, purebred dogs, and small breed dogs do get adopted quickly so we encourage interested parties to apply online.

Please apply here:

http://texasgreatdane.org/adoption-application/

http://www.wagsandwhiskerspetrescue.com/adopt.html

Meet Juno! Our 10 year old pit bull mix that we received on December 23rd of 2020. When we first got Juno from Bakersfield we could tell she was going to need lots of medical attention. Despite the fact that she walked with a slight limp, the thing that caught our attention the most was the large masses hanging from her body; one on the chest, one in the middle of her abdomen, and another one hanging off her nipple on the back right side. She has a couple other battle scars and struggles with stairs due to arthritis but that sure doesn't stop her. Juno has a very young soul and loves to play, especially with other dogs. When we received her, she was being housed with a smaller scruffy dog but he got adopted rather quickly, leaving her to anxiously wait for her forever family to come and find her. Next week she is scheduled for surgery, dental cleaning and bloodwork, she would love to be able to heal in a comforting home! If you're interested in meeting the lovely Juno to adopt or foster, submit an online application and we will get back to you ASAP, she'll be waiting!

If you are interested in meeting this pet please apply to adopt at
http://www.wagsandwhiskerspetrescue.com/adopt.html
if the pet is still available for adoption and you are approved to adopt we will contact you to set up a meet and greet appointment.

animal.description:
Wile E. Coyote is a German Shepherd with a ton of personality - we call him ‘Wiley’ and he’s been an awesome addition to his foster family’s pack. Wiley is about 2.5- 3 years old and weighsin at 80 pounds. He ended up at the shelter as a stray and his family chose not to reclaim him. Wiley has adjusted well to living with a female GSD in his foster home. He is incredibly sweet and loves to meet people. Wiley doesn’t show any sort of negative reaction to new people or dogs. He is incredibly smart and knows basic commands well. He knows sit, stay, shake, down and drop it. Like other dogs, he can get very excited and has a tendency to jump during his excitement but he’s getting better. He’s been working to stay down when he meets people as he’s quite tall! He has not been placed in a crate during his foster time and has done quite well free roaming the house. He’s been allowed on furniture and the bed in the house so will need to be trained if his forever home does not want him on furniture. Wiley loves walks, fuzzy toys and can play with sticks/fetch forever. Like most GSDs, he will need a lot of exercise and mental stimulation. While he was anxious and fearful at the beginning, Wiley has become a very gentle dog in his few weeks in a good family environment. He hasn’t had much experience being left alone but has shown no signs of being destructive. 

Finally, Wiley has hip dysplasia in his left hip. He has a tendency to be sore after intense playing and doesn’t like to be touched on his back legs or tail. He has been prescribed pain killers as needed - he was evaluated and does not require surgery. He will need to be kept on joint supplements and at a lean weight. His foster parents have worked extensively with him on familiarizing Wiley with positive touch. Wiley can be reactive with his mouth - he’s very particular about how much time you spend petting him and will growl at you or show his teeth if he doesn’t want you touching him. He immediately stops after you pull your hand away but he will use his teeth to nip you if he’s uncomfortable with any touch he doesn’t like. Small children might not do well with Wiley as kids will need to know when to stop touching Wiley and how to be respectful of a big dog’s space. 

Overall, Wiley is an incredible dog and will make a great companion. He will require consistent attention, as most GSDs do, but he will quickly become a member of your pack.  He makes hilarious noises, loves to ‘sing’ with ambulances, is a big cuddler, and loves to sit on your feet. His foster family loves him dearly and is excited for his goofy self to find an incredible forever home for him. 

Adoption fee includes: spay or neuter, all routine vaccines, heart worm testing, fecal test and microchip.

Many questions can be answered by going to www.gsrescue1.org

animal.description:
Scroll down to learn more about this pet:

***
Bichon and Little Buddies is open only

by appointment with a completed application.
Dogs in foster homes require an appointment and approved application to meet. The application is online at http://www.bichonrescues.com/pre-adoption-form-dog If a dog is listed as available, then we are still taking applications - no need to email or call to ask about the status. Note: The forms that Petfinder or Adopt-a-pet has to inquire about the dog is not our application application. Our form must be filled out to be approved to adopt a pet.***

Covid-19 Precautions:

Until further notice, Bichon & Little Buddies will be doing all meets and adoptions by appointment only. To be able to control the number of people at the shelter at one time, we will be suspending our open hours on Thursdays. If interested in adopting, please fill out the pre-adoption application and we will set up a time for you to come meet the dogs you are interested in.

About this Dog:

Name: Girlie

Breed: Chihuahua type mix

Approximate Age: 8-10 yr

Gender: Female

Weight: 14 lb

Adoption Fee: $250

Why in Rescue: Texas Transfer

General Profile: Please fill out the adoption application at http://www.bichonrescues.com/pre-adoption-form-dog if you are interested in meeting one of our dogs.

Girlie is a quiet old girl who made the long trip from Texas after her owner died and the family members weren't able to keep her. We are estimating her to be between 8-10 years old. We had her teeth cleaned, and are treating an ulcer on her eye. She does have a heart murmur, so that needs to be monitored to see if she would benefit from medication in the future. At this time she doesn't show any signs of heart failure. We don't know if she lived with children, but there were other small dogs in the house so she may do fine with other dogs. We don't know if she is housetrained. If interested in adopting this older girl, please fill out the pre-adoption application.

We do our best to evaluate the dogs while they are with us, but they sometimes act different in the shelter environment than they do in a home. If you are interested in any of our dogs, please fill out the pre-adoption application and we will set up a time for you to come and meet them.

If considering adopting a former breeding dog, the following article is good to read to help you understand the special needs these dogs may have. http://www.nowisconsinpuppymills.com/mill-survivors.html

Adoption Procedures:

1. Completely fill out the pre-adoption application at http://www.bichonrescues.com/pre-adoption-form-dog. We will be checking with your vet if you have had pets, calling your landlord (if any) and checking a personal reference, before we contact you about visiting the adoptables. Any missing information may have us moving onto another application.

2. If you application is approved, we will contact you to come meet the adoptables that you are interested in.

3. If it is a match, you will complete the adoption contract and pay the adoption fee. Please be prepared to take your adopted pet home when you come meet him/her. In most cases, you will be able to take the pet home the same day. If all the vetting hasn't been done yet, we will hold the pet for you until the vet work is completed.

4. If you have filled out an application and we haven't contacted you within a week, we may have missed your application, the pet may have been adopted by another applicant, or you may have been missing information on your application. You may contact us to find out the status of your application at this time. Please give us a week to process your application before contacting us!

The adoption fee through Bichon and Little Buddies Rescue is $200 - $475 depending on the age of the dog, which includes Wi State Sales Tax. Included in this fee is your new companion who will be spayed/neutered, have a current Certificate of Veterinary Inspection (as required by state law), current on age appropriate vaccinations, heartworm tested and started on preventative, microchipped, and dewormed. Other medical needs will also have been taken care of, such as dentals and treating ear infections.

To assist you and your new pet in adjusting to life together, you will also receive an 8 week age appropriate obedience training course at For Pet's Sake Dog Training for $50 (up to $200 value). You may opt to take Puppy Kindergarten, Adult Beginners, Small Dogs Big Hearts, or Shy & Reactive Dog Class. You must start the class within 90 days of adoption for the reduced fee. For more information on the classes visit www.forpetssake.cc

All dogs are seen BY APPOINTMENT ONLY. Many are in various foster homes getting extra one on one attention getting them ready for their new homes. The first step in adoption is filling out the pre-adoption application. Bichon and Little Buddies is run by volunteers who have full time jobs in addition to the hours they spend with the rescue dogs. Having an application on file assures us that the potential adopter is really interested in adopting a dog. It also assists us in placing dogs in homes where both the dog and new owners are happy. The application puts you under no obligation to adopt a dog from Bichon and Little Buddies.

The Dog Pre-Adoption Application can be found at http://www.bichonrescues.com/pre-adoption-form-dog

Thanks for thinking about adopting your new pet!More important information:

***We are a Wisconsin based rescue and do not ship our pets. If you are considering adoption you must be willing to drive to meet and adopt the pet, as well as bring the pet back to us if the adoption doesn't work. We adopt primarily in WI and IL, but will consider applicants in MN, IA, and MI.***

***Please do not set up an appointment to meet the animals until you are ready to take your pet home. If the meeting results in a match, you can often take the dog/cat home the same day or within a couple days if the medical care hasn't been completed. We are not able to hold pets for adopters beyond this time. Thanks for understanding.***

***While we hope all of our adoptions lead to permanent homes for the animals we place, sometimes things just don't work out. We do have a 30 day trial period. For the first 30 days, if you or Bichon and Little Buddies decide that the adoption isn't a good match for either the humans or the pet, the adoption fee will be refunded minus $50 within 30 days of the return of the dog. Bichon and Little Buddies also requires adopters to return the pet to us at any time that they are unable or unwilling to care for the animal anymore.***

***We do not show dogs/cats without an appointment. The first step in adoption is filling out the pre-adoption application at http://www.bichonrescues.com/pre-adoption-form-dog Please do not call/email until AFTER you have filled out an application.***

Bichon and Little Buddies is a State Licensed Rescue # 268555-DS

Salsa has had a rough start to her life and is looking for a home that will show her how to trust.  She is a gentle soul, affectionate, and bonds deeply with her human, however she is extremely skittish and takes awhile to warm up.  Once she lets you in she is very loving and sweet. 

She is looking for a forever home that is quiet, patient, and overwhelmingly positive.  She is fearful and will need to be given a lot of time to decompress and get settled in her home and new routine.  A home with experience in working with a rescue dog is preferred.  She is ok with other dogs, and looks to them for guidance, but could also be the only dog in the home.  

Salsa would prefer to be in a home without children or cats.  She would love to have her own fenced in yard, where she can go in and out of the house as she pleases.  This sweet girl deserves to have the best life!

If you are interested in adopting, and would like to make an appointment for a meet and greet, please fill out and submit our Canine Adoption Application on our website:

https://www.apsfh.com/adoption-program/canine-application/

animal.description:
TEDDY, neutered male, 6-months-old, 17-lbs

If you would like to give TEDDY a forever home, please log onto 
abetterchancerescue.org To fill out online application

Teddy is very affectionate and friendly, he’s loving by nature.  He enjoys being around people, he’d follow foster mom everywhere around the house.  He’s also friendly and playful around other dogs and cats, either in public place or indoor.  He can easily adapt to new environment.  His favorite pastime is hanging out in the park with his buddies and daily walks.  Teddy is crate trained to sleep overnight, not a barker.  He will do best for household looking for an additional companion dog, since he’s so playful and loves doggie companions.

About Teddy's rescue:
Teddy was abandoned at the shelter.  We did not have the heart to leave this cute little guy behind, so we bailed him out of the shelter and start preparing him for adoption.  He has received a clean bill of health after a complete physical check.

Please watch Teddy’s YouTube videos below:
Teddy’s profile
http://youtu.be/ebwH75LXbnM

Temperament:  
Energy level:  Medium 
Ideal home environment: Quiet or active both 
Is the dog good with strangers:  friendly
The dog is best with children of what age group? Over 6-yo

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.OUR REQUIREMENTS FOR PUPPY ADOPTION:
1) PUPPIES WILL ONLY BE PLACED IN HOMES WITH YOUTHFUL, PLAYFUL, DOGS. This helps integrate the dog into your household easier by giving the pup a mentor.
2) In addition to the youthful playful dog, someone MUST also be home at least part of the day. Please do not apply for a puppy if you are gone 8-10 hours a day. It is not a good situation for you or the puppy.
3) You must have plans in place to socialize your puppy properly.
4) Our puppies are not livestock dogs. They must be family pets that are allowed inside the home.

Please watch this short video which demonstrates how puppies learn polite behavior from their adult dog mentors. https://youtu.be/R6N8STRl2aI

Meet Levi! This handsome little cutie is a hoot!

Watch him determinedly splash and bite water out of his big water bowl! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nCCQsGWF9P8

And this video shows when he first arrived to his foster home, and he adorable gets used to being the focus of paparazzi. https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Y2a-URjcw58

Levi is a fine-boned puppy who weighed about 50 pounds at seven months of age. His ideal adult weight is likely around 75 pounds.

Although the shelter put his birthdate at March 2020, all indications are that he is a little younger than that, born closer to May 2020.

Little Levi loves to play! He gets along easily with the other big dogs in his foster home. He likes them all! He has a blast romping and wrestling with them. He must have at least one large, playful doggie companion in his forever home. If you don't already have a suitable fur buddy for him, adopt one from us!

At this young age, Levi is really energetic. He can be rambunctious at times. For this reason, any children in the home should be older than age seven or so.

Levi is totally house trained. He can be crated, but it is not needed. He goes in easily when you just put him in, close the door, and say "we're done."

He is polite on leash and needs a little more practice to perfect his technique. He rides happily in a car.

He is a "landscaper!" He will dig a crater in your yard to lay in.

Little Levi is such a delightful, sweet dog. He will be a great forever companion for the right family.

SPIN Pyrs are all in foster homes in the Dallas/Fort Worth area. Potential adopters are asked to make travel arrangements if they live elsewhere. All SPIN dogs are spayed or neutered, current on vaccinations and on heartworm prevention. Please go to our website www.SpinRescue.org and fill out an application for this great Great Pyrenees!

animal.description:
****Please do not send us inquiries/emails asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. See the bottom of this bio for more FAQs regarding our adoption process before emailing.****

Name: Silvia aka Tatum

Age: approximately 1-2years old

Weight: 70 pounds

*Adoption Fee: $375.00

*Health: up to date on Vaccines, spayed, microchipped

MEET SILVIA:
She is the Total Package ! She loves going for Long Walks, Snuggling on The Couch, Staring Deep into Your Eyes & giving Big Bear Hugs ! 
This sweet girl loves to learn. Tatum will require some basic training she also has some slight separation anxiety so she will need a family that is willing to take the time and help her understand it’s okay to be alone sometimes. Tatum will do best in a home with a large yard so that she can have plenty of space to run and play. She would love a family that is active and want a buddy for adventures. Tatum gets along well with relaxed dogs that will not overwhelm her. 

To apply to adopt Tatum , fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES: $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
If you are interested in adopting Spicy, please email meganniewold@gmail.com

Do you scroll past the puppies and yearn for a dog who already knows the basics like how to potty outside and not to pull on a leash? Do you want to go the extra mile with training and help a dog learn to trust strangers and be less protective of her loved ones? That's what Spicy wants to learn because she has the basics down pact! Spicy knows how to sit, stay, come, lay down, she's potty trained, she walks well on a leash, ignores people and dogs on walks, and knows "down! when she gets jumpy. She's as smart as they come-but we won't lie to you, Spicy is looking for the right kind of forever home. 



Spicy is a four-year old, 40 pound, boxer mix! She has big paws and a big head to match her giant personality! 



Spicy can be fearful of new people and new situations but her foster family is setting her up with the right training to give her the confidence to meet new strangers with confidence. Since being in her foster home, Spicy has blossomed into the sweetest dog her foster family has ever had (don't tell their resident dog!) 

She has grown to love both her foster mom and foster dad as well as her foster dog-brother. Spicy's current home doesn't have kids but Spicy has been tested with kids and loves them; We recommend 15+ household for Spicy as she learns to accept new people into the house. She loves to go on long walks around the neighborhood and play chase with her foster-dog brother in the backyard. Her foster mom thinks she would do best as the only dog in the home because although Spicy is dog-friendly, she can be somewhat toy and food possessive. Right now, Spicy goes on three long walks a day and still gets the zoomies-so she needs an active household who can take her on lots of long walks, skipping the dog park, since she can be finicky toward certain people. 

Spicy will need continued training to teach her that the people who come into her new family's home are friends and should be trusted and not feared. Her foster family has been working on this and have had success-Spicy is smart and can definitely be trained! 

Finally, Spicy's foster mom and dad want her potential family to know that the work you put into Spicy will come back to you in so much love. She loves her people hard and is the sweetest, silliest little girl that will be the best dog a family could want! Oh yeah, did we mention she LOVES bath time? 

Sponsored by Brian, Stephanie, & Winston (fka Tux)

animal.description: Angus is a friendly and affectionate boy who, like many of us, has been put through the ringer this year. Hes made great progress, but its time for him to find a committed foster or adopter to help him continue the healing process outside of the shelter. Angus isnt asking for much- in fact, rest is the main prescription from the clinic vets. No long walks or rowdy shenanigans for this guy! If you have a calm, quiet home where Angus can relax and continue to heal, please ask about helping him today!

animal.description:
Buddy T. is a 10-year-old male German Shepherd Dog who was found stray in Southern California. He was covered in dirt, starving and had open sores on his ears. Shelter staff found him to be a social boy who was very eager for human attention. Buddy walked past the many stressed and barking dogs in the shelter, remaining focused on the people around him. Buddy had an accident at some point, resulting in a shortened tail that he was wagging in circles to show how appreciative he was of receiving love and medical treatment. TSGSR staff visited Buddy and found a gentle giant with a big personality. Buddy is now being cared for by TSGSR volunteers at Thulani Central. He rides well in the car, gets along with other dogs and is good with middle school aged children as well as adults. He has leash manners and obeys basic commands. Thulani volunteers all love to walk and brush Buddy! He has a personality that pulls people in and makes them smile. He will make a wonderful addition to a family with love to share.

Buddy T. Summary:
- Buddy is a neutered male, 10 yrs old, weighs 71 lbs, current on shots
- Good with Adults, middle school aged children, dogs, and travel in the car
- Young Children and cats TBD

Buddy passed a set of evaluation tests before being accepted into the TSGSR. The tests are not intended to assess how smart the dog is but are important for TSGSR to determine if the dog is expected to be safe in a family home. The tested behaviors check to see if the dog will guard or protect food or toys from people, will tolerate handling all over its body (including ears, nose, lips to check teeth, lifting paws, belly, back, and gently pulling the tail) and the ability to get along with other well behaved dogs. He remained calm during all of these tests and showed no aggressive tendencies. 

Please join us in welcoming Buddy to TSGSR! Check back often. We will be updating his bio as we learn more about him!

What's Next for Buddy T.:
Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR) will continue to see that Buddy is well cared for and receives all medical care needed for his well being while in our care. In addition, TSGSR is beginning a search for an adoptive home that will care for him for the rest of his life. He will come to his new home with a supply of food, a cushy pad if wanted, and other goodies such as toys. 

Buddys medical expenses will be covered for the rest of his life by Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR)!

If you want to learn more about Buddy, or are interested in possibly providing an adoptive or foster home, please send us a message by clicking on the "Ask About Me" button. We will often get feedback or "updates" from a dog's foster home and as any updates become available they will be included here.

If you are reading about him on Petfinder.com sometimes an available YouTube video is not listed. If this occurs you can still view the video by pasting its URL into a new browser window or tab.

Available Video URL(s): https://youtu.be/0sYT1Zx8pQ8

Saving one dog wont change the world. It will change the world for that one dog.

Freckles is currently living in a foster home. Please submit an application and we will link you up for an intro!

Freckles is eligible for a foster-to-adopt period to ensure a perfect match for our favorite guy!

Age: ~3 years
Weight: ~70lbs.
Housebroken: Yes!
Crate trained: Yes, he does very well with his crate-training
Dog sociability: Not a match, leash reactive (barks/lunges at other dogs)
Cat sociability: Not a match
Kid compatibility: Not a match
Ideal living situation: Freckles prefers a quiet neighborhood without a ton of passing dogs. He would ideally love a backyard to call his own. He is not a match for a high-rise/elevator building.

Meet Freckles! This handsome guy with the most boopable nose has been a volunteer favorite at One Tail for a while and once you meet him, you'll know exactly why! This guy is a bundle of love. He loves companionship and is happy to play with stuffed toys, zoom around the yard, or just get couch cuddles while you binge The Bachelorette. Freckles is very treat motivated and has many tricks in his repertoire already and is eager to learn even more! Check out the videos in his profile to see him in action. If you're ready to give all your love to one 'n only - then Freckles is your guy!

His adoption fee is now sponsored due to a generous donation from one of his fans, and he is neutered, vaccinated, heartworm negative and microchipped. 

**Due to COVID, we are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application.**

animal.description:
Are you looking for a loyal companion to face the new adventures in the new year? Gia may be the pyrfect girl for you! Although Gia is still young, she is a mature and well-mannered girl. Over the holidays, she is committed to working on her basic cues and perfecting her leash manners, in preparation for her furever family. Like many of our pyrs, Gia is wary when people approach her quickly without warning, and/or with loud noises. However, once she bonds with you, she transforms into the most attentive and loyal companion. Gia prefers to hang out with dogs of similar size, but she is also quite content with being by herself. She is playful at times, and is also perfectly happy to chill and take it easy. Gia will do well in a relatively quiet home where her people will spend the time to get to know her, and help her get settled into her new environment. If you are willing to let Gia into your heart, she will no doubt be your most loyal companion!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
NGPR dogs are in foster homes throughout the U.S., NOT Beacon, NY. View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed.

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.
animal.name: Gia - Well-Mannered Girl!

animal.description:
Barnabus is currently living in a foster home. Please submit an application and we will link you up for an intro!

Barnabus is eligible for a foster-to-adopt period.

Age: ~ 1.5 years
Weight: ~ 50 lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate Trained: Yes, but takes some time to settle
Dog Sociability: Not a match, leash reactive (barks/lunges at other dogs on walks)
Cat Sociability: Not a match
Kid Compatibility: May do well with kids 12+. Too rowdy for littles. 
Ideal Living Situation: Barnabus would love an active adopter excited about training! He requires a yard in his forever home to set him up for success.

Barnabus is so much fun! This guy is wicked smart and loves to engage his brain with enrichment toys and training. He has picked up on several tricks like sit, down, shake, and "puppy pushups". He will do almost anything for a piece of hot dog! He loves to play and is a bit clumsy and might run into tables and doors when he is not paying attention. animal.description:
Big Bubba is living in a foster home. Submit an application from our website and then make an appointment to meet him.

Bubba is not eligible for foster and will be a straight adoption.

Age: ~5 years
Weight: ~72lbs
Housebroken: Yes
Crate trained: Takes time to settle in his crate (10-30 minutes). Has done well with free roam while his fosters have been away.
Dog sociability: Leash reactive/frustrated. Barks, lunges at other dogs on leash. 
Cat sociability: Not a match
Kids: Not a match
Ideal home: Big Bubba is looking for a quiet neighborhood without a ton of foot traffic. He is a big boy that will do best with a confident handler. He takes time to warm up to strangers and would love a patient adopter with a fridge full of snacks :)

Big Bubba is gentleman looking for a lap to sleep in forever. He is 90% head and 10% body. He is an angel in the house--he asks permission to get onto the furniture for his snuggles, he is potty trained, and he doesn't even sniff the trash. He knows a plethora of fun tricks, including sit, stay, shake, and roll over! Bubba is not sure yet about city life, and would love to be an only dog for now. He will require a confident handler who is willing to work with him on his leash reactivity and pulling and some stranger danger. We think he could also love having a yard to sniff around--he sniffs like a cartoon dog! He would love nothing more than to sit in your lap all day, or snooze tucked into his bed with a blanket next to you. 

Bubba's adoption fee is 300. He is netuered, up to date on core vaccines, microchipped and heartworm negative.

***We are receiving a much higher than usual number of adoption applications. We ask that you please be patient and someone will be in touch via email within 72 hours. Please do not email us unless you have not received a response in 72 hours. Please only fill out one adoption application. ***

animal.description:
Let me tell you about Gus. Do you like big dogs? Have you always wanted a pony, but your HOA didn't allow it? Well, Gus is about the size of a small pony. He's tall and lanky. He's only 10 months old and 1/2 lab so you know he's still a little rambunctious, with knees and elbows flying everywhere. He has the sweet, curious temperament of a lab. He has no idea his size and will try to sit on top of you if he can. He's also a pro counter-surfer. He currently is very thin and weighs 62 lbs. He is eating 8 cups of puppy food a day. I think he's happy to have the extra groceries. Gus is also 1/2 ridgeback. He has a perfect ridge all the way down his back. Gus is heartworm negative, and fully vetted. He doesn't chew things and isn't destructive at all. He gets along with my dogs, although they get tired of his playful energy. If you walk him daily (he's a great leash walker), he's calmer in the house. Gus likes to be wherever you are. He is not a fan of the crate, but does well sleeping on the floor in our bedroom at night. We take our dogs outside throughout the day, and Gus has quickly figured out the house training bit. Gus should go to an active home, who will exercise him regularly. 

Gus is a male Lab/Rhodesian Ridgeback that is around 10 months old and currently weighs 73 lbs.

animal.description:
Rubydoo is one active girl looking for a family to match her energy. Rubydoo was given away by her family and then was caught running stray shortly after. Her original family did not want her back so she came to TAPS. Despite a little bit of bouncing, it has not broken Rubydoo's spirit. She has definitely never met a stranger. 



Rubydoo will need work on obedience and manners but her enthusiasm for life will make you forget she's not supposed to be jumping up on you. Due to her "I love you, I love you, I love you" spirit, she would do best in a home without small children because she would definitely knock them down with kisses. 



Potty training and crate training unknown.



UPDATE: Rubydoo rides well in a car, but needs help getting into taller vehicles. She rode so well in my car and did not try to get in the front seat and simply enjoyed the ride and fell asleep. In my home, she was active, lively, very sweet and is quiet comfortable in a home setting. She will jump on your furniture and run through your house with her zest for life and loved having lots of toys to play with, but seemed most content with a nylabone. Rubydoo will need obedience training as she is very "mouthy" and needs to be taught that a dog toy is a proper chew toy (rather than your arm, and presumably furniture). She did not have any accidents in my home and gave a subtle message that she needed to go outside by walking around my back door so potential adopters may need to help her with potty training.

animal.description:
Lotus is about 45 lbs. She looks like a miniature American Bulldog with a very sweet and shy disposition. She is about 7 years old and lived a very sad life. She was very malnourished and forced to breed constantly to the point where she had mammary tumors which have been removed and biopsied. Thankfully they were benign. She does not care for other adult dogs, but her energy completely shifts when she sees a puppy. Surely because she had so many she bonded with taken from her :( Lotus is looking for a family who will love her and respect her.  She loves toys, balls, bones as she was deprived for so long. We hope more than anything to find the person or family who can give Lotus the life she deserves. We would even love if someone would be open to fostering her which requires no adoption commitment and no fees are associated with fostering
After the terrible life she lived, she is still so incredibly sweet, loving and easy going. If you are open to fostering this sweet girl and helping change her life forever, please email us for more information.

animal.description:
Bosley is a 1 year old tri-color pit/ lab who is looking to be somebody’s best friend.

 Bosley is a wonderful dog, loves every single human he meets, loves kids, and would like to find a new human that lives an active lifestyle that Bosley could join. 

He needs to be the only dog in the home, so he will not be placed in a home with other dogs - while he is not reactive and doesn’t lunge at other dogs on the leash 
 he has displayed signs of not always playing well with others and has shown signs of aggression with my older dog... therefore he will do best as an only dog. When it comes to humans, he has never met a human he doesn't like, he is the friendliest and happiest dog in the world. He loves cats, however he plays rough as he is still young and most cats tend to not favor his style of playing. He is e-collar trained, loves swimming, going for jogs, knows how to sit, stay, come, down, etc ...

 Bosley is still a puppy so he is high energy, of you are looking for a slow, calm, minimal energy dog Bosley is not the right dog for you. If you are looking for a dog that loves to go for jogs, will play fetch as long as you let him, will go on road trips, camping, etc ...

 Bosley would be perfect, he has done all of these things with me! While he wouldn’t make the best guard dog (he’s kind of a wimp) he has made my home feel very safe by barking when necessary and doing his best to play the part. I’m not in a rush to find Bosley a home, however I know that there is someone else who can provide him with a more suitable lifestyle than I can.
 Bosley used to go to work every day with me, unfortunately we now have new rules which prevents Bosley from being able to come with me ... being confined from 8am-8pm just isn’t fair to a puppy, so I am having to make this very difficult decision.

animal.description:
Christmas- yes that’s her name- wants to bring holiday cheer to your family all year long! This sweet, spunky and beautiful girl has spent most of her puppy hood recovering from surgery on her back legs. She gets stronger every day and now it’s time for her to be the puppy she never got to be! She is destined to grow into a beautiful and loving Pyr. Christmas is incredibly well trained and knows tons of commands. She is also crate trained, housetrained and leash trained. She loves being with her humans and has never met a stranger. Despite her mobility constraints Christmas loves to play with canine companions. She will do best with dogs her size or smaller so that they don’t risk hurting her. She needs assistance getting in the car or up on the couch, but her mobility is getting better and it hasn’t stopped her from being an energetic love bug. Christmas has so much love and cuddles to give her new family - apply for this beautiful girl today to add Christmas joy to your family all year round!

NYS Registered Rescue # RR102
View full listing, fee and online application at - www.nationalpyr.org/adoptable-dogs (sorry, no phone submissions, but if you would like more information you can email us at renpyrgroup@yahoo.com).

Secure VISIBLE fencing is required; invisible fencing WILL NOT contain this breed. 

Our goal is to assess every application on its own merits. Key considerations are: 1) the experience of the applicant with large breed dogs 2) children in the household or regularly visiting the household are ready for a large-breed dog who is a guardian by nature (www.nationalpyr.org/know-the-breed) and 3) the sex of other dogs currently residing in the household to avoid same-sex aggression issues. For puppies under six months old, the applicant’s ability to socialize the puppy with older dogs is a priority.

animal.description:
Daina is a 7 year old, gorgeous, red colored, floppy eared, curly tailed Anatolian Shepherd/Red Bone Hound Mix that is looking for someone to love and care for her for always. Daina was left with a person in a temporary status, but sadly her owner ended up not being able to take her back so she has come to rescue to find her new home. She is of course house trained, crate trained and walks well using a harness. She knows sit, shake down and command (go to crate). She will bark to alert you but doesn't dig or chew on anything that she shouldn't. Daina enjoys a good snooze on the couch and is super happy to cuddle and netflix with you on a rainy day. She's good with kids and cats but needs a proper introduction to doggy friends to make sure everyone is friends. She is super friendly, a true gentle giant, she’s not really interested in toys but is super food motivated and loves any kind of treat. This sweet girl cannot wait to find her new home and she hopes her family will come along soon and swoop her up!

animal.description:
Meet Bandit. This 1 year old, young, smooth coated Saint Bernard boy is looking for a new place to lay his paws. Bandit has gone through a rough patch with the loss of an owner and then was surrendered to a local shelter. He is a bit confused and nervous with all these changes in his life so the shelter reached out to us in order to get him into a foster home to decompress and to start healing. Bandit is quite submissive and unsure of pretty much most things as he's not been exposed to much. He will need a fur sibling in his forever home as not only does he take comfort from them but he takes guidance and cues from their behaviors and reactions. Bandit is a good boy and he will be working on gaining confidence, leash walking, potty and crate training and any other skills he might need to get ready for his forever home. If you think Bandit is the guy for you and you're looking to grow your furry family, let us know!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.This handsome tripod is Scooby. While Scooby is missing a rear leg (we don't know why; he came to us this way- with a badly broken other rear leg), it doesn't slow him down one bit. In fact, a very smart, skilled vet once told us "dogs are born with three legs and a spare" and it's true; Scooby is proof. He can run and play the same as any other dog- and he loves other dogs (cats are an unknown but we can cat test upon request).

Scooby is current on his vaccinations and deworming, is microchipped and neutered and his broken back leg has been surgically repaired and has no issues. He is fostered in Jacksonville, and his adoption fee is just $250, which includes all of the aforementioned vetting.

Home visit and reference checks are required and are NOT negotiable.

animal.description: Duncan is an 1-year-old male Black Lab mix who has already been neutered. He is a return adoption because his energy was more than his adopter could handle. Duncan is a very handsome fellow. He has a super shiny black coat with a little white markings on his chest. Duncan weighs 41 pounds and we believe he will be a medium sized adult dog. He is very frisky, active, and has boundless energy! Duncan will need a nice yard with a sturdy fence where he can safely play and exercise. This sweet boy would be just fine in a home with children and other dogs. For Duncan to have a successful adoption, his adopters must understand that he is a great dog who will need some patience with his silly puppy like antics. Duncan has the potential to be a fantastic family dog with a family who will just help him to reach his full level of awesomeness.Dog/puppy adoption fees are $120 and cat/kitten adoption fees are $50. Our adoption fees cover a microchip, microchip registration, discounted spay/neuter certificate, deworming, vaccinations (as age and law requires), and a courtesy vet exam at participating offices. Chocolate Chip is a golden doodle who is 5 to 6 years old. He was surrendered by his owners to the local dog pound, and then GRRR picked him up from there. Chip was very thin and a matted mess, and the pound had to shave him down.

Chip had a mass removed that turned out to be a rare follicular cancer, but luckily one that has a good prognosis with good margins. He did get very good margins, so he should be just fine. He is an incredibly good boy with just the sweetest temperament and loves everyone he meets.

Chocolate Chip has a potential home, but if he does become available we will let you know here. If you too would like to become a foster to adopt home, please read our adoption policies. If you qualify, just write our adoption team for an adoption application. During the holidays, we are not sending out new applications for adoption. We hope this will change soon after the first of the year.

animal.description:
Jack is a special dog very close to our hearts here at Hail Mary Rescue. At 6 weeks old, Jack and his siblings were brought to 501c in Southeast Louisiana that advertised as a Sanctuary. For SIX YEARS they were locked in a 10x10 kennel with limited interaction except with each other. We took out Jack and his brother, Jerry, July 2020 while others went to different rescues. After several months of rehab with both dogs, Jerry found his forever home where is doing excellent. Jack is still with us and we are looking for the following home to open their hearts for this dog who has gone through so much. Must have a friendly dog for Jack to hang with. He thrives on following and playing with other dogs. Must have patience and allow Jack to bond with you in his own time. Please consider him. He is truly worthy of a home.

Hail Mary Rescue doesn't just have Southern Dogs. We have CAJUN Southern Dogs!! The smartest, strong hearted, "Get back on your feet after being knocked down hard", dogs there are. Just like our Cajun ancestors. Now if we can just teach the younger generation to spay/neuter, our Cajun Dogs wouldn't have to go through so much just to stay alive.

Hail Mary Rescue, a 501c3 non profit, saves dogs from southeast Louisiana shelters. It is a foster-based rescue which gives pets the opportunity to live in home settings where they are house and crate trained, learn basic obedience commands, and are well socialized, many with children and other dogs. Exposure to cats depends on the foster's home. Adoption fee is $200 for LA adoptions; $400 (includes transportation fee for out-of-state adoptions). All dogs are completely vetted, vaccinated, spay/neutered, and micro-chipped prior to adoption. See your new best friend? Submit an application today https://form.jotform.com/92111104800135 A volunteer will contact you usually within 24 hrs.

Though we do our best in trying to answer all emails in a timely manner, sometimes things get away from us, get lost or misplaced. It is never our intention to ignore a request about an adoptable animal in our facility.

Sandy Brown, Director, PAW Animal Shelter

animal.description:
Everybody clear the way for Keno!  This boy is HUGE weighing in at 150 pounds.  Keno is a Lab/Mastiff mix who was rescued from a shelter in Kentucky, after being surrendered by his owner who had too many doggies.  Keno is roughly 7 years old, has the stature of a lab but the mass of a Mastiff. 

Keno is a complete love bug for sure.  He loves to give kisses and curl up next to your feet and even in your lap.  That’s right, this 150 pound dog is a big ole lapdog!  Keno has meet a variety of dogs in his foster, definitely prefers the very low key seniors and is over the hyper ones lol!  We believe Keno may have been large and in charge at his former crowded home.  

This guy is ready to live out his golden years as your own and only.  He says he has had enough of being the big man of the house. 

Keno would do best with a fenced in yard as he is very strong and needs some leash work.  He is friendly to people but would most likely knock the little kiddos down as he is strong.  Keno seems to be house trained and has had zero accidents inside.  This hunk is very sweet, dog friendly, and could stand to lose some poundage, but don't tell him I said that!

Once at our vet's office, this poor sweetie tested positive for Lyme, but that hasn’t affected his happy personality one bit!  Lyme is a tick borne disease that is not contagious to other dogs or humans but will remain in his system, throughout his life.  Keno may have an occasional flare-up which would be indicated by joint pain/inflammation, limping, lethargy and possible loss of appetite.  Typically a dose of antibiotics is enough to make the disease go dormant again.  To help control the Lyme, Keno will need a yearly Lyme vaccine.  Should he have multiple flare ups in a short amount of time, his kidneys could be affected.  Lyme has become more prevalent in the southern states, and many dogs with this disease have lived long happy lives!

All HART dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped and up to date on all vaccines, including bordatella and rabies.   They are heartworm tested and on preventative for heartworm, fleas, and ticks.   If you are interested in any of our pets, you must complete an online dog adoption application   at www.rescueAhart.org .   The application will put you in touch with this wonderful dog's foster family so you can schedule a meeting.   Thanks!   www.rescueAhart.org

animal.description:
Charlie was used as a fighting dog, and she spent the last 2 years in a rural shelter getting overlooked. A few weeks ago, Philly Bully Team posted for a foster, and we weren't sure how long it would take to find one since Charlie needs to be an only pet and since some people may be turned off by her history. Thankfully, her foster mom sent in an application almost immediately, and she even drove 18 hours to pick Charlie up so she wouldn't have to wait a few weeks for transport. 

Since arriving less than 3 weeks ago, Charlie has made huge strides. She's opened up to her foster family and their friends, and she has settled in beautifully (which is all the more remarkable considering she had never been in a home before). She warms up to people very quickly and gives a ton of Charlie kisses. Despite her horrific past, Charlie is thriving and spreading her love to every human she meets. Her happiness and energy are absolutely contagious. 

If you are interested in adopting, please fill out an application on our website: www.phillybullyteam.com

He came into the shelter on Dec. 18 as a lost dog with ID, but his family could not be contacted -- that's why it's so important to keep microchip information up-to-date with a new address or phone number. He is a very sweet dog and super cute, very calm and easy going and great on a leash. His family is no doubt searching for him. Little Bit is about 3 years old and weighs 60 pounds. He has not been neutered yet, but the vet will see him soon. He is up-to-date on vaccinations and will be heartworm tested upon adoption. Come meet him in Run 86 using ID#626518.

Please note, all of the pet listings on Friends of Shelter Animals for Cobb are done by volunteers, not shelter staff. If this pet came in as lost (not an owner surrender), we don't know how they might be with children, other pets, or if house trained. You can bring your pet to the shelter for a meet & greet with your potential new best friend. When calling the shelter about a cat or dog, please use THE ID NUMBER, names are oftentimes made up by volunteers. 

This pet and many others are available for adoption from the Cobb County Animal Shelter 1060 Al Bishop Dr. Marietta, GA 30008, call (770) 499-4136 for more information. Shelter hours are: Tues. - Sun. 10:30 a.m. to 4:30 p.m. by appointment only until further notice, CLOSED Mondays & Holidays.

animal.description: Greta is the most beautiful brindle girl with the sweetest personality! We think she is around 3 years old and a Shepherd mix. She is as sweet as can be and revels in human attention. Greta loves to ride in the car and enjoys her two times a day walks without much pulling on leash. She is house trained, has good house manners and is good in the crate. Greta is well behaved for baths and gentle taking treats. She gets along with all the dogs she has met and likes to play, but doesn't need another dog in her forever home to be happy. If you think you are ready to add to your family by adopting Greta when she is ready for adoption, then fill out an adoption application on our website today! We recommend completing the application process and connecting with a adoption coach before looking for a dog or puppy you'd like to adopt. If you're already approved to adopt or if you've adopted from Labs and More before, connect with your adoption coach for the next steps. Your interest in adopting a rescued dog or puppy from Labs and More Rescue is appreciated! Please find our adoption information at www.labsandmore.org. Your adoption donation provides funding for Labs and More, a nonprofit organization which is supported solely by Volunteers and funded by donations. Good news is your adoption donation can be considered tax deductible. So much care is provided to your new dog prior to the adoption, including: spay and neuter, microchip, veterinarian visit(s), vaccinations, and other medical care as needed. Many of the dogs we rescue require extensive surgeries and care prior to adoption. Please understand we are unable to predict future behavior or medical needs of your adopted dog. We provide no guarantees regarding behavior, breed, or age of the dogs. Thank you for rescuing.Thank you for looking to Adopt a Labrador Retriever or other Mixed Breed Dog from California Labradors Retrievers and More Rescue. Please take a moment and go to www.labsandmore.org and click on Adopt to complete our online dog adoption application. If you have any questions email us at doginfo@labsandmore.org or call us at 858-273-5386. Thank you for looking to a rescue group to fulfill your dream of adding a new dog to your life! Dogs + Love = Family

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Judy is a young-at-heart spry 8-year-old Shepherd mix (possibly with Corgi given her coloring and short legs). She was surrendered to our rescue in December after her owner (who recently adopted her from Eastern WA) determined her behavior needs were too much to handle. Specifically, Judy is leash reactive to dogs and the gal lived in an apartment in the city. Judy has no history of biting people or dogs. Upon evaluation it was evident that Judy was not dog aggressive but just unsure of how to greet other dogs. She did well with a structured walk and slow dog introductions and is currently in a foster home with a dog and a cat. Judy is friendly with people and would benefit from a single family residence (no apartments) and an experienced family who can provide leadership to help her feel secure. We will share more information about Judy once we get to know her in foster care.

Foster Updates:
Judy is a human friendly loving companion. On walks with a training collar she can walk by other dogs with some anxiety (whining) and is improving on a daily basis. In the home she ignores the resident dog (no aggression). She is a bit too curious with the cat so probably better in a feline free house. No issues with any humans or kids. Good in the crate!

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $350 which includes spay/neuter, all core vaccinations, microchip, heartworm test and health certificate. Your adoption fee may be tax deductible as Dog Gone Seattle is a federal 501c3 organization.

Apply online: www.doggoneseattle.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Sadie is a 6-7 year old 35 lb mixed breed who was surrendered to the rescue in December as it had become increasingly apparent to her owner that she was uncomfortable and stressed in the busy household with toddlers. Sadie has no history of aggression but would thrive in a calm and quiet household as she can be an anxious girl. She is very dog social and soft, but will benefit from a quiet but confident human to help her with her confidence. Sadie would likely do fine in a home with a cat as well. She is house trained and generally quiet. She was diagnosed at 2 years with IBD though further diagnostics such as food trials were not explored. Her IBD is generally easy to manage with a bland diet and she is not on medication but when she is stressed she can have flare ups. We will share more info about Sadie as we get to know her in foster care.

Foster Updates:
Sadie is shy and guarded at first but once she trusts you she is just the sweetest, affectionate and friendly. She would probably enjoy a dog buddy in the home. She is quiet and good in the crate.

Diet Info: Upon intake to our rescue Sadie received a Nutriscan for food allergies due to her history of "tummy issues." Results indicate sensitivities to corn, turkey and fish. Sadie is currently eating a lamb based food and has had no issues or flare ups.

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $350 which includes spay/neuter, all core vaccinations, microchip, heartworm test and health certificate. Your adoption fee may be tax deductible as Dog Gone Seattle is a federal 501c3 organization.

Apply online: www.doggoneseattle.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Eileen is a miracle.

Eileen was abandoned with her brother Elliott in Southeast Missouri and during her spay surgery, it was discovered she had a Diaphragmatic Hernia, which most likely occurred when hit by a vehicle. 

Eileen had emergency surgery on Monday, 12/21, and has bounced back quickly. She is anxious to get her life moving forward and a family of her very own is at the top of her holiday list.

Eileen has the best personality and temperament, constantly giving kisses and leaning in for pets.  She will crawl right in your lap as if she is a tiny lap dog.

Did we mention Eileen is absolutely gorgeous? Her photos do not do her justice. 

Eileen survived a vehicle incident, her heart slowing during prep to be spayed and then emergency diaphragmatic hernia surgery.  The universe must have something very special planned for her.

IF SERIOUS, PLEASE APPLY AT WWW.K9EI.DOG, DO NOT SEND PETFINDER INQUIRIES.  

Update: 
Happy Holidays, 

We asked people on her Petfinder Bio to not Petfinder inquiry with us as we do not return those inquiries and instead apply for the dog.  We received a dozen applications for Eileen within an hour of posting her and we review the applications for approval in the order we receive them.  Once we have approved applications we make calls to interview potential adopters.

Our adoption application is located online at www.k9ei.dog.  If your application is approved, you will be given the opportunity to meet the dog following an interview. 

I can tell you that Eileen has 4 weeks of recovery ahead of her which entails crate rest, leash walking to potty, and then back inside the home, she must wear the cone for 4 weeks to protect against licking her incision which is large. The incision must be kept dry and checked for infection daily. She needs to have an ice pack held on the incision 3 times daily to keep swelling down for the first 7 days following surgery.

Eileen should not climb stairs or be jumping to prevent the stretching of her skin where the incision runs along the whole of her body. It's vital to her recovery to not developing an infection or the opening of the incision. 

She is 9 months old and even with her breathing taxed before surgery, she was a very active dog.  She is a mix of Great Pyrenees and mystery dog, she is small compared to a purebred GP.  She does have the sense to wander away from home as they were bred to be on ranches/farms protecting livestock.  When healed she will need exercise and adventure to keep her happy.  

She is not trained in any way shape or form.  Most likely she and her brother were put out by breeders or wandered away from the breeder's home.  The surgeon's best guess is she was struck by a vehicle that pushed her stomach, liver, and intestine up into her ribcage placing pressure on the heart.  

The surgery consisted of removing the organs and placing them in their correct position, mending the diaphragm, removing scar tissue, performing a second surgery of sewing her stomach into place to prevent bloating, and then they finished by spaying her.  

Despite the intensive surgeries, she returned to her happy go lucky self by the late night.  Tail wagging, smiles, walked outside the hospital to potty, eating fine and allowing for icing of the incision 3 times a day.

This is all we know about Eileen, her brother is very much similar and doing well in his foster to adopt home.  He has the same fun-loving free spirit personality. We do not know how she is with other animals, she shows no reaction to dogs passing her in the hospital cage, nor has she been around children.

Thank you for your interest,

Cynthia

animal.description:
MEET CHIP 5!!

From Chip's Foster: Chip is awesome. Sometimes we call him Chipper Dipper! I love him alot. We got him from a dog shelter in Ohio when he was three months old on Mother's Day. They got him from an overcrowded shelter in Alabama. We moved to Arizona a year ago. That's how he got here! He and I did training together. He is very smart but at times when overly excited forgets his manners. He will jump up but if you are consistent he knows your expectations, but each person has to let him know jumping up is not ok. He loves treat rewards. He gets water spray bottle as consequence only if needed. He is still a puppy mentality so will chew things he shouldn't if you are not checking on him. He loves to chew on non rawhide bones. He especially lives to play fetch and will bring ball back. He will look for the ball if you say go get your ball. His favorite command! He can sit, stay, step up, lay down, come, walks nice on leash but would be even better if we took more walks. He has no problem with a gentle check of his teeth or ears. He does well with groomer trimming his nails and once he is in the bath he seems to enjoy a warm bath. We use halter collar for his walks. He is fenced, and needs to be to keep him safe. He prefers to be inside. He has only been an inside dog. He is crate trained while we are gone and for bedtime. He is ok in cars, just not his favorite thing. He loves to be with me and will follow me if he doesn't see me but does not get separation anxiety. He is not an off leash dog when out in community or hiking. He tends to eat fast so we use a slow down bowl but I think it's so he can go and try to get the other two dogs food if they walk away. He needs to be only dog. He has become aggressive toward my other two dogs regarding food and attention from us. He has never been people aggressive. Never. He's a good boy just wants all our love. He will cuddle, likes to sit right next to me touching or when on the floor he will lay on my foot. I love that. He is healthy, current on all vet care but I have found that foods can cause him an skin allergy that looks awful. I haven't had him allergy tested. He has micro chip. He has had excellent get care. He would make a couple or single person who will give him lots of time, love and activity a wonderful pet. Again he should be the only pet. Should not go to home with someone planning to start a family or someone who is gone alot. Oh, he is potty trained. We have a doggy dog that he uses , but he prefers to have us open it. I think it's because he is tall but again he uses the doggie door. If you want a loving, incredible well loved never harmed dog, Chips your man. , We will ask for rehoming fee and will need to be comfortable with applicants in the household to ensure commitment to him, time for him, that he will be only dog and that he will be safe and well cared for. If this sounds like you it could be a great match for Chip!

If you are interested in meeting this dog, please visit our website for our online application www.underdogaz.com

PLEASE NOTE: This dog is courtesy posted for another individual or Rescue. Different policies and fees may apply.

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Bunz is a 55-60 Lab / Pit Bull mix that was rescued from a high kill shelter in Victor Valley CA. He is estimated to be around 2 years old and will join us on December 20th. More info to come once he arrives and settles in!

Seattle Foster update: Bunz is a playful pup that walks well on a leash. Bunz does need someone willing to explore training to help him overcome his excitability and learn to focus as he lacks handler awareness. Many dogs that have been shuffled through homes and shelters were never given the opportunity of a proper learning environment so they end up bringing many of their puppy like behaviors into adulthood. Bunz does very well when the handler promotes leadership in the relationship. Bunz is dog friendly but needs guidance in regards to manners when around them.

If you have natural leadership capabilities, are willing to provide structure and guidance for Bunz, he will be a wonderful companion for years to come in return.

Bunz currently lives with a cat and a dog and is not aggressive towards them but still needs a lot of guidance from his handler.

Adoption Info: Adoption fee is $500, which includes spay/neuter, current rabies/DAPPV/bordetella vaccinations, microchip, health certificate, and heartworm test. All adoption fees are donations to a Washington non-profit corporation and all donations go to benefit the animals in our rescue.

Apply online at www.DogGoneSeattle.org

Animal History: This dog was rescued from euthanasia at a high-kill shelter in California and will be available for adoption in Seattle, once evaluated in a loving foster home in the greater Seattle area.

animal.description:
UPDATE: Sweet Kahlua had her ACL surgery January 14th and has started an arduous 12 weeks of recovery.  Sadly, the damage was much more extensive than we anticipated.  Kahlua has obviously been suffering and in pain for quite some time.  
We are so very thankful to Dr. B at Healthy Pets Animal Hospital who performed this intricate surgery to give Kahlua a new start at life.  We are also beyond grateful for her wonderful foster parents, Nita and Robert, who graciously took this deserving dog into their home and are loving Kahlua like their own.  They have also committed to nursing her through her rehabilitation.  
We appreciate your prayers as Kahlua heals and stays strong in the months ahead!

Welcome KAHLUA! This beautiful, gentle sweetheart has joined us just in time for Christmas! Kahlua is about 6 years old, was raised with a family with children, knows basic commands and is the perfect house pet.  Still plenty playful, she loves to play fetch, tug-o-war, and loves her walks. She adores children and reportedly gets along fine with other dogs.
Sadly, Kahlua lost her home because she needs ACL repair surgery that the family could not afford.  When Northwest German Shepherd heard her story, we just had to step in to help.  Kahlua will have ACL repair surgery in a few weeks and then will recuperate in her loving foster home.  
We will keep her profile posted as she heals and gets ready for a fresh start in a new home.

Meet Lulu!  As you can see from her photos, Lulu has the soulful eyes of a Beagle! They will draw you in and make you fall in love.  But before you get lost in those big brown Bette Davis eyes listen up.  Lulu is a strong-willed girl who know what she wants.  But what she wants and what she needs are not always the same thing.  

Lulu will need an owner who is a strong leader, as she desires to have direction and thrives when given it.  She has been through basic obedience and has proven to be very intelligent.  If you are a strong and calm leader for her, she will repay you by climbing right into your lap for snuggles.  She is very affectionate with her humans, loves to play with them, and loves to be outdoors with them.

Like all goddesses, she does have one tragic flaw.  She's an opportunist. While she thrives under strong leadership, she will take advantage of any opportunity she can when it comes to calling the shots.  Basically, if you give her an inch she will likely roll her cute little barrel body all over it.  Like most alphas we know in this world, there are those who are meant to be in charge, and then those who WANT to be in charge but should not be. This is the case with our Lulu. In her head she is just doing what comes natural to her.  This is why she needs a person who will not mind reminding her she did not get that promotion she hoped for as boss lady of her new home.

If you would like to be considered to adopt Lulu, please complete the adoption application for Lulu online here: http://www.doubledogrescuevolunteers.org/adoption_application.php?dog=Lulu
(please reach out to KateS@doubledogrescue.org if you run into any issues with the application process).

For specific questions about Lulu, please contact Michelle at michelled@doubledogrescue.org.

animal.description:
Please take a moment to read Lennon’s special letter to Santa to learn more about our sweet boy!

Dear Santa,
 
Lennon here, writing to you since my friend Lisa, our trainer, says I’m the BEST boy and am definitely on your nice list. Some of my favorite things are car rides, snuggles, and walks in the woods, but what’s at the top of my wish list is a forever home!
 
I haven’t always had it easy, Santa. I came from North Carolina as a puppy, and was adopted quickly cause I’m great! My family took good care of me and tried their best but I got a medical problem called Immune Mediated Thrombocytopenia when I was first with them. It was hard for me and I know it was hard for them (my friends at the SPCA can tell you more about it. I’m only 3, I don’t get those big words!).
 
I got better and for a while I was doing great. Playing and running with my family. But then this summer I got sick again; I had to go potty a lot. Lisa said it’s like I ate bad take-out, whatever that means. I got real skinny and I now wear a jacket to stay warm and toasty. 
 
My family tried so hard to help me but it was just too much for them. So they made the tough decision to bring me back to the SPCA. The docs here gave me more medicine and tried some more tests. And then, they figured out what could be wrong! It looks like I could have inflammatory Bowel Disease / Food Allergies. I’m on some meds and doing much better, (Although, I still go potty a lot) but I still have a ways to go ’til I’m 100%. So, Santa, this year I would like a foster-to-adopt home; this is a neat thing where someone falls in love with me, brings me home, helps me get fully healthy while the shelter pays the bills and takes care of all that, and then when I’m all good they officially adopt me!
 
So just to recap, Santa: super handsome dog, goodest boy in all the land (per me), looking for a low-key kinda home with a fenced yard (and maybe a doggie door so I can go out whenever I need to!), a couch to curl up on, and a person or people to snuggle with.
 
Work your magic, Santa! And maybe your elves here on social media can SHARE my letter to help my wish come true – tell everyone to email Lisa at trainer@spca914.org for more info or to meet me! Can’t wait!!
 
xoxoxo, Lennon

Due to Covid-19 the SPCA is allowing adoptions by appointment only. If you’d like to discuss an animal and/or set up a meet and greet please email shelter@spca914.org with your competed application and a copy of your driver’s license or a government issued ID. Please allow up to 72 hours for a response! Thank you for your understanding! 


Adults dogs over 1 year of age: $225-$375
All Puppies: $375
Seniors and Lonely Hearts Club members: $85

Please visit: https://spca914.org/adopt/adoption-process to read our Adoption Policy and Procedures in full.

Feel free to e-mail shelter@spca914.org or call (914) 941-2896 ext. 11 with any questions or for more details on the dog(s) in which you are interested.

NYS Registration # RR056

animal.description:
My name is Leo. Don't you just love my beautiful golden mane and my amber eyes?? I am 2-3 years old. I've been in rescue for 4 months. Before that I was at the Humane Society in Topeka, KS. I was adopted twice but I was returned to the Humane Society both times. My adopters didn't pay enough attention to me so I kept escaping my yard and went looking for friends. I really love people and attention! I'm a pretty chill guy and like being petted, but I'm not in your face about it. If you scratch my neck I will close my eyes and lean on you. I am very gentle with my Pyr Paw. Sometimes I even put up two paws and I almost fall over backwards in the process! I'm house trained, like to go for walks, and I like to play in the water. I like treats and will sit for them. Other dogs are my friends and I would prefer a female in my new home. My foster dad introduced me to cats at the vets office and I paid them no mind. I do require a 6 ft fence so I don't go on walkabouts. I will come to you microchipped, neutered, up to date on vaccinations, and up to date on heartworm and flea/tick preventatives. I really need my next home to be my Furever home. I'm ready to make a family really happy! 

Applicants must have a secure and visible fence. In order for your application to be approved, you must also pass a home check and a vet check which includes having at least a two year vet history. Children in my home need to be 10 years of age or older. I can be adopted in Missouri and surrounding states: Illinois, Iowa, Kansas, Nebraska, and Arkansas. My rescue is able to transport me to those states. If you would like to give me a furever home, please fill out an application on my rescue website. 

Being fostered in Holden, MO
